$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Contrast

::Q-CON-001:: Medicare eligibility is based mainly on age (65 and older), while Medicaid eligibility is based mainly on income. {TRUE #### Medicare is primarily for people 65+, whereas Medicaid eligibility is based on income and household size.}

::Q-CON-002:: Medicaid is primarily intended for people with low income. {TRUE #### Medicaid provides health coverage to eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities.}

::Q-CON-003:: Medicare's basic rules are set separately by each individual state. {FALSE #### Medicare is a purely federal program administered nationwide by CMS, so its basic rules are the same in every state.}

::Q-CON-004:: Medicaid is funded jointly by the federal government and the states. {TRUE #### Medicaid is a joint federal-state program; the federal share is set by the Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FMAP).}

::Q-CON-005:: Medicare is administered nationwide by CMS, a federal agency within HHS. {TRUE #### Medicare is administered by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS), a federal agency within HHS.}

::Q-CON-006:: Original Medicare is the main program that pays for long-term nursing home (custodial) care. {FALSE #### Medicaid, not Medicare, is the primary payer for long-term services and supports; Original Medicare generally does not cover long-term custodial care.}

::Q-CON-007:: Medicaid is the primary payer for long-term services and supports in the United States. {TRUE #### Medicaid is the nation's primary payer for long-term services and supports (LTSS), including nursing home care.}

::Q-CON-008:: Parts A, B, C, and D are all parts of Medicare. {TRUE #### Medicare has four parts: A (hospital), B (medical), C (Medicare Advantage), and D (prescription drugs).}

::Q-CON-009:: Medicaid is divided into Part A and Part B, just like Medicare. {FALSE #### Medicaid does not use the lettered Part A/B/C/D structure; that structure belongs to Medicare. Medicaid's companion program for children is CHIP.}

::Q-CON-010:: Medicare Part C (Medicare Advantage) plans are offered by private companies approved by Medicare. {TRUE #### Medicare Advantage (Part C) is an alternative to Original Medicare offered by Medicare-approved private companies.}

::Q-CON-011:: CHIP provides low-cost health coverage to children. {TRUE #### The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) provides low-cost coverage to children in families that earn too much for Medicaid but cannot afford private insurance.}

::Q-CON-012:: A person can be enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid at the same time. {TRUE #### People enrolled in both programs are called 'dually eligible' individuals, so a person can have both at once.}

::Q-CON-013:: For someone enrolled in both programs, Medicaid pays first and Medicare pays last. {FALSE #### For dual eligibles, Medicare pays first for services it covers and Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort.}

::Q-CON-014:: Medicare Part B requires a monthly premium. {TRUE #### Medicare Part B (Medical Insurance) requires a monthly premium; for 2026 the standard premium is $202.90.}

::Q-CON-015:: Because Medicaid is run by the states, eligibility and covered benefits can vary from state to state. {TRUE #### Each state administers its own Medicaid program within federal rules, so eligibility details and benefits can vary by state.}

::Q-CON-016:: Which program is primarily for people age 65 and older? {
=Medicare #Medicare is the federal program primarily for people age 65 and older.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is based on income, not age.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not seniors.
~The Health Insurance Marketplace #The Marketplace sells private plans; it is not an age-based program.
}

::Q-CON-017:: Which program bases eligibility mainly on a person's income? {
~Medicare #Medicare is based mainly on age, not income.
=Medicaid #Medicaid eligibility is based mainly on income and household size.
~Medicare Part C #Part C is a way to receive Medicare benefits, still age-based.
~Medicare Part D #Part D is Medicare drug coverage, still age-based.
}

::Q-CON-018:: Which statement best describes how the two programs are administered? {
~Both are purely federal and uniform nationwide #Only Medicare is uniform; Medicaid varies by state.
~Both are run entirely by the states #Medicare is federal, not state-run.
=Medicare is federal and uniform; Medicaid is state-run and varies by state #Medicare is administered federally by CMS (uniform nationwide), while Medicaid is administered by each state within federal rules (so it varies).
~Medicare is state-run; Medicaid is purely federal #This reverses the two programs.
}

::Q-CON-019:: How is Medicaid funded? {
~Entirely by the federal government #Medicaid funding is shared, not purely federal; Medicare is the purely federal program.
~Entirely by state governments #States share the cost with the federal government, not alone.
~Entirely by employer premiums #Employer premiums fund commercial insurance, not Medicaid.
=Jointly by the federal government and the states #Medicaid is funded jointly by the federal government and the states, with the federal share set by the FMAP.
}

::Q-CON-020:: Which agency administers Medicare across the country? {
=The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) #Medicare is administered nationwide by CMS, a federal agency within HHS.
~Each state's health department #States administer Medicaid, not Medicare.
~The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) #The IRS handles taxes, not Medicare administration.
~Private insurance companies acting alone #Private companies offer some plans but do not administer the federal program.
}

::Q-CON-021:: Which program is the main payer for long-term nursing home care in the U.S.? {
~Medicare #Original Medicare generally does not cover long-term custodial care.
=Medicaid #Medicaid is the nation's primary payer for long-term services and supports, including nursing home care.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not long-term care.
~Commercial insurance #Commercial plans rarely cover extended long-term care.
}

::Q-CON-022:: A patient needs several years of custodial nursing-home care. Which program is most likely to pay for it? {
~Medicare Part A #Part A covers short inpatient hospital stays, not long-term custodial care.
~Medicare Part B #Part B covers outpatient and doctor services, not long-term care.
=Medicaid #Long-term custodial care is generally paid by Medicaid, the primary payer for long-term services and supports.
~Medicare Part D #Part D covers prescription drugs, not long-term care.
}

::Q-CON-023:: Which list correctly names the four parts of Medicare? {
~Part 1, Part 2, Part 3, Part 4 #Medicare parts are lettered, not numbered.
~Part A and Part B only #A and B are only Original Medicare; C and D also exist.
~Part A, Part B, Part C, Part D, and Part E #There is no Part E.
=Part A, Part B, Part C, Part D #Medicare has four parts: A, B, C, and D.
}

::Q-CON-024:: Medicare Part C is also known by what name? {
=Medicare Advantage #Medicare Part C is also called Medicare Advantage, offered by Medicare-approved private companies.
~Medigap #Medigap is separate supplemental insurance, not Part C.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is a different program entirely.
~CHIP #CHIP is the children's program on the Medicaid side.
}

::Q-CON-025:: What does Medicare Part D cover? {
~Inpatient hospital stays #Inpatient hospital care is Part A.
=Prescription drugs #Medicare Part D is optional prescription drug coverage offered through private companies approved by Medicare.
~Long-term nursing home care #Long-term care is mainly covered by Medicaid.
~Doctor office visits #Doctor visits are Part B.
}

::Q-CON-026:: Which statement about Medicaid's structure is correct? {
~Medicaid is divided into Parts A, B, C, and D like Medicare #Lettered parts belong to Medicare, not Medicaid.
~Medicaid only covers prescription drugs #Medicaid covers a broad range of services, not only drugs.
=Medicaid has no lettered parts and pairs with CHIP for children #Medicaid does not use lettered parts; its companion program for children is CHIP.
~Medicaid is identical to Medicare #The two programs differ in eligibility, funding, and structure.
}

::Q-CON-027:: Whom does CHIP primarily cover? {
~Adults age 65 and older #Seniors are served by Medicare, not CHIP.
~Military veterans #Veterans have separate VA coverage.
~Large employers #CHIP covers children, not employers.
=Children in families that earn too much for Medicaid but cannot afford private insurance #CHIP provides low-cost coverage to children in families earning too much for Medicaid but unable to afford private insurance.
}

::Q-CON-028:: Which statement about cost is true? {
=Medicare Part B has a monthly premium #Medicare Part B requires a monthly premium ($202.90 in 2026), plus deductibles and coinsurance for many services.
~Medicare is always completely free #Medicare usually involves some cost, such as the Part B premium.
~Medicare never charges any premiums #Part B does charge a premium.
~Only Medicaid charges premiums #Medicare, not Medicaid, is the program with regular premiums.
}

::Q-CON-029:: For a person with very low income, which program typically costs the patient little or nothing? {
~Medicare #Medicare usually involves premiums and cost-sharing.
=Medicaid #Medicaid is designed for people with limited income and generally costs the beneficiary little or nothing.
~A commercial PPO plan #Commercial plans charge premiums.
~Medicare Part C #Part C is a Medicare option and can involve costs.
}

::Q-CON-030:: People who are enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid at the same time are called what? {
~Dependents #A dependent is a person covered under another's plan.
~Subscribers #A subscriber is the primary policyholder of one plan.
=Dual eligibles #People enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid are called dually eligible (or dual eligible) individuals.
~Self-pay patients #Self-pay patients have no insurance coverage.
}

::Q-CON-031:: For a dual-eligible person, which program pays first for a covered service? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort, paying after Medicare.
~CHIP #CHIP covers children, not dual-eligible adults.
~The patient pays first #Coverage pays before the patient is billed for covered services.
=Medicare #For dual eligibles, Medicare pays first for services it covers.
}

::Q-CON-032:: The phrase 'payer of last resort' for dual eligibles refers to which program? {
=Medicaid #Medicaid is generally the payer of last resort, paying after Medicare and other coverage.
~Medicare #Medicare pays first, not last.
~Commercial insurance #Commercial insurance is not the dual-eligible context here.
~CHIP #CHIP is the children's program, not the last-resort payer.
}

::Q-CON-033:: For dual eligibles, Medicaid often helps pay which Medicare costs? {
~Nothing at all #Medicaid does help with Medicare costs for dual eligibles.
=Medicare premiums and cost-sharing #For dually eligible individuals, Medicaid helps pay Medicare premiums and cost-sharing and covers gaps like long-term care.
~Only prescriptions bought outside the U.S. #Medicaid's help is not limited to drugs purchased abroad.
~Hospital meal charges only #Medicaid's assistance is far broader than meal charges.
}

::Q-CON-034:: Which statement correctly contrasts the two programs? {
~Medicare is income-based; Medicaid is age-based #This reverses the two programs.
~Both are age-based #Only Medicare is age-based.
=Medicare is age-based; Medicaid is income-based #Medicare is based mainly on age (65+), while Medicaid is based mainly on income.
~Both are income-based #Only Medicaid is income-based.
}

::Q-CON-035:: A financially well-off 70-year-old retiree is generally eligible for which program? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid is income-based; a well-off person generally would not qualify.
~CHIP #CHIP is for children.
~Neither program #Age 65+ qualifies a person for Medicare.
=Medicare #Medicare eligibility is based on age, so a 70-year-old qualifies regardless of income.
}

::Q-CON-036:: A low-income 30-year-old parent with little income might qualify for which program? {
=Medicaid #Medicaid is income-based, so a low-income adult may qualify even though they are far from age 65.
~Medicare #Medicare is mainly for people 65+ or with certain disabilities.
~Medicare Part B #Part B is a component of Medicare, still age-based.
~Medicare Advantage #Medicare Advantage is a Medicare option, still age-based.
}

::Q-CON-037:: A Medicare Advantage (Part C) plan typically bundles which coverage together? {
~Only Part A #Advantage plans include more than just Part A.
=Part A, Part B, and usually Part D #Medicare Advantage plans are bundled and include Part A and Part B and usually Part D drug coverage.
~Only prescription drugs #Drug coverage is usually included but is not the whole plan.
~Only long-term care #Long-term care is generally a Medicaid responsibility.
}

::Q-CON-038:: Why can Medicaid benefits differ depending on the state you live in? {
~Because Medicaid is federally uniform #Medicaid is not federally uniform; that describes Medicare.
~Because hospitals set Medicaid rules #States, not individual hospitals, run Medicaid.
=Because each state runs its own Medicaid program within federal rules #Each state administers its own Medicaid program within federal requirements, so eligibility and benefits can vary.
~Because benefits are priced by ZIP code #Variation comes from state administration, not ZIP-code pricing.
}

::Q-CON-039:: Which program has essentially the same basic rules in every state? {
~Medicaid #Medicaid varies by state.
~CHIP #CHIP is state-administered and varies.
~Employer-sponsored insurance #Employer plans differ by employer.
=Medicare #Medicare is federally administered by CMS, so its basic rules are uniform nationwide.
}

::Q-CON-040:: Which is a key difference in what the two programs cover? {
=Medicaid, not Medicare, is the main payer for long-term care #Both cover doctors and hospitals, but Medicaid is the primary payer for long-term care, which Original Medicare generally does not cover.
~Only Medicare covers doctor visits #Both programs cover doctor visits.
~Only Medicaid covers hospital stays #Both programs cover hospital care.
~Neither program covers preventive care #Both cover preventive services.
}


$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Cross-Domain

::Q-CRS-001:: What is the correct order of the basic healthcare claims process? {
=Patient receives care, provider submits claim, payor processes payment #The claims process flows from patient receiving care to the provider submitting a claim to the payor for processing and payment.
~Payor submits claim, provider receives care, patient processes payment #Payors do not submit claims -- providers do.
~Provider receives payment, patient submits claim, payor delivers care #Providers submit claims, not patients, and payors do not deliver care.
~Patient submits claim, payor delivers care, provider receives payment #Patients do not submit claims to payors -- providers do.
}

::Q-CRS-002:: After adjudication, which of the following is a possible outcome for a healthcare claim? {
=The claim is approved for payment #After adjudication, a claim may be approved for payment, rejected (returned for correction), or denied (service not covered or does not meet policy requirements).
~The claim is forwarded to the patient for self-processing #Patients do not self-process claims; the payor adjudicates them.
~The claim is automatically resubmitted by the payor #Payors do not automatically resubmit claims; rejected claims are returned to the provider for correction.
~The claim is sent to a different provider for review #Claims are not sent to other providers for review; the payor makes the adjudication decision.
}

::Q-CRS-003:: What is the purpose of a HIPAA 270 transaction? {
~To submit a claim for payment #Claim submission uses the 837 transaction, not the 270.
=To verify a patient's insurance eligibility and benefits #The HIPAA 270 transaction is an electronic eligibility inquiry that a provider sends to a health plan to verify a patient's coverage and benefits.
~To send payment from the payor to the provider #Payment information is communicated through the 835 (ERA) transaction, not the 270.
~To report a HIPAA privacy violation #The 270 transaction is for eligibility inquiries, not for reporting privacy violations.
}

::Q-CRS-004:: Every healthcare claim must pair which two types of codes? {
=A diagnosis code (ICD-10-CM) and a procedure code (CPT or HCPCS) #Every claim must pair a diagnosis code (ICD-10-CM) explaining why care was needed with a procedure code (CPT or HCPCS) describing the service performed.
~A National Provider Identifier (NPI) and a Social Security Number #While the NPI must appear on claims, it is not paired with a Social Security Number. Claims require diagnosis and procedure codes.
~A facility code and a pharmacy code #Facility codes and pharmacy codes are not the required code pairing on every claim.
~A payor code and a clearinghouse code #There is no standard 'payor code' or 'clearinghouse code' that must be paired on a claim.
}

::Q-CRS-005:: What is the difference between an Explanation of Benefits (EOB) and a bill? {
=An EOB is a summary of how the health plan processed the claim; it is not a bill #An EOB is a document sent by the health plan to the patient summarizing how the claim was processed. It is not a bill -- the patient should compare it to the actual bill from the provider.
~An EOB is the final bill the patient must pay to the health plan #The EOB is not a bill and does not require direct payment to the health plan.
~An EOB and a bill are two names for the same document #They are different documents; the EOB summarizes claim processing while the bill requests payment from the patient.
~An EOB is sent by the provider, while a bill is sent by the payor #The EOB is sent by the health plan (payor), not the provider. The bill comes from the provider.
}

::Q-CRS-006:: What is an Electronic Remittance Advice (ERA)? {
~A document the payor sends to the patient explaining their benefits #The document sent to the patient is the Explanation of Benefits (EOB), not the ERA.
=A HIPAA 835 transaction the payor sends to the provider detailing payment, adjustments, and denial reasons #The ERA (HIPAA 835 transaction) is sent by the payor to the provider after claim adjudication, detailing the payment amount, adjustments, and reasons for any denials.
~A claim submission form the provider sends to the payor #Claim submissions use the 837 transaction. The ERA is a payment notification sent from payor to provider.
~An eligibility verification request sent before a patient visit #Eligibility verification uses the 270/271 transaction, not the 835.
}

::Q-CRS-007:: What is the 'allowed amount' in healthcare reimbursement? {
~The total amount the patient must pay out of pocket #The allowed amount is the plan's maximum payment, not the patient's total out-of-pocket cost. The patient owes only their cost-sharing portion.
=The maximum amount a health plan will pay for a covered service #The allowed amount is the maximum a health plan will pay for a covered service. For in-network services, the provider generally cannot bill the patient beyond this amount.
~The amount the provider charges before any insurance processing #The provider's charge (billed amount) is different from the allowed amount, which is set by the health plan.
~The fee a clearinghouse charges to process a claim #The allowed amount relates to reimbursement for services, not clearinghouse processing fees.
}

::Q-CRS-008:: What is the primary role of a healthcare clearinghouse? {
~To provide medical care directly to patients #Clearinghouses do not provide medical care; they are data intermediaries.
=To receive transactions from providers, convert them to HIPAA-standard formats, and forward them to health plans #A clearinghouse acts as an intermediary that receives claims and other transactions from providers, converts them into HIPAA-standard electronic formats, and forwards them to the appropriate health plan.
~To issue National Provider Identifiers to new providers #NPIs are issued by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS), not by clearinghouses.
~To adjudicate claims and determine payment amounts #Claim adjudication is performed by the payor (health plan), not by the clearinghouse.
}

::Q-CRS-009:: What does 'TPO' stand for under HIPAA, and why is it important? {
=Treatment, Payment, and Operations -- covered entities may share PHI for these purposes without patient authorization #TPO stands for Treatment, Payment, and Health Care Operations. Under HIPAA, covered entities may share protected health information for these three purposes without obtaining patient authorization.
~Transaction, Privacy, and Oversight -- it describes the three HIPAA rules #TPO does not stand for Transaction, Privacy, and Oversight. It refers to the permissible uses of PHI.
~Testing, Processing, and Output -- it describes how claims are adjudicated #TPO is not related to claims processing steps. It is a HIPAA concept about when PHI can be shared.
~Transfer, Protection, and Organization -- it defines how clearinghouses operate #TPO does not describe clearinghouse operations. It defines when covered entities can share PHI without authorization.
}

::Q-CRS-010:: Which standard format is currently adopted under HIPAA for electronic healthcare transactions? {
~HL7 FHIR Release 4 #HL7 FHIR is an interoperability standard for health data exchange but is not the HIPAA-mandated transaction format.
=ASC X12 Version 5010 #ASC X12 Version 5010 is the current HIPAA-adopted standard format for electronic healthcare transactions, used by providers, payors, and clearinghouses nationwide.
~ICD-10-PCS Version 2024 #ICD-10-PCS is a procedure coding system for inpatient settings, not a transaction format.
~CPT Category III codes #CPT Category III codes are temporary procedure codes, not a transaction format standard.
}

::Q-CRS-011:: The National Provider Identifier (NPI) is a unique, permanent 10-digit number that carries no information about the provider's location, specialty, or type. {TRUE #### The NPI is intelligence-free, meaning the number itself carries no information about the provider. It serves purely as a unique identifier.}

::Q-CRS-012:: HIPAA's Privacy Rule applies only to health plans and does not cover healthcare providers or clearinghouses. {FALSE #### HIPAA's Privacy Rule applies to all three types of covered entities: health plans (payors), health care providers, and clearinghouses.}

::Q-CRS-013:: The HIPAA minimum necessary standard requires covered entities to limit PHI disclosures to the smallest amount of information needed to accomplish the intended purpose. {TRUE #### The minimum necessary standard is a core HIPAA principle requiring that when PHI is used or disclosed, it must be limited to the smallest amount needed for the purpose.}

::Q-CRS-014:: A claim submitted without a valid ICD-10-CM diagnosis code will still be processed for payment as long as a procedure code is present. {FALSE #### A claim submitted without a valid ICD-10-CM diagnosis code is returned to the provider as incomplete and will not be processed for payment.}

::Q-CRS-015:: Standardized transaction formats allow any provider to submit a claim to any health plan using the same data structure, enabling interoperability across the healthcare system. {TRUE #### Standardized formats ensure that any provider can communicate with any health plan using the same data structure, which is the foundation of interoperability in healthcare.}

::Q-CRS-016:: In the basic claims flow, the provider submits a claim to the payor after the patient receives care. {TRUE #### The standard flow is patient receives care, then the provider submits a claim to the payor for reimbursement.}

::Q-CRS-017:: Providers may submit claims to payors using any proprietary format they choose, as long as the claim data is accurate. {FALSE #### HIPAA requires providers to submit claims electronically using HIPAA-standard transaction formats, not proprietary formats.}

::Q-CRS-018:: Automated edits performed on incoming claims check for completeness, valid values, duplicate submissions, and beneficiary eligibility. {TRUE #### Before adjudication, payors run automated edits that check for completeness, valid values, data consistency, duplicate submissions, and provider/beneficiary eligibility.}

::Q-CRS-019:: A rejected claim and a denied claim mean the same thing in healthcare billing. {FALSE #### A rejected claim is returned to the provider for correction and can be resubmitted, while a denied claim means the service is not covered or does not meet policy requirements.}

::Q-CRS-020:: Since January 1, 2013, HIPAA operating rules require health plans to respond to eligibility inquiries in real time. {TRUE #### HIPAA operating rules effective January 1, 2013, require health plans to respond to electronic eligibility inquiries in real time, including deductible, co-pay, and coinsurance information.}

::Q-CRS-021:: A payor will approve a claim as long as a valid procedure code is present, regardless of the diagnosis code submitted. {FALSE #### Payors use the diagnosis code to determine medical necessity. If the diagnosis does not support the procedure according to coverage policy, the claim may be denied.}

::Q-CRS-022:: Patients should compare the Explanation of Benefits (EOB) they receive from their health plan to the provider's actual bill to check for accuracy. {TRUE #### An EOB is a summary of how the plan processed the claim, and patients should compare it to the provider's bill to verify the amounts are correct.}

::Q-CRS-023:: The Electronic Remittance Advice (ERA) is sent from the provider to the payor to explain why a claim was submitted. {FALSE #### The ERA (HIPAA 835 transaction) is sent from the payor to the provider, not the other way around. It details payment amounts, adjustments, and denial reasons.}

::Q-CRS-024:: For in-network services, a provider generally cannot bill the patient beyond the allowed amount set by the health plan. {TRUE #### In-network providers have agreed to accept the health plan's allowed amount as the maximum charge. The patient may owe cost-sharing (co-pay, coinsurance, deductible) but not charges above the allowed amount.}

::Q-CRS-025:: A provider's NPI number changes whenever the provider moves to a new state or changes specialties. {FALSE #### The NPI is permanent and does not change based on location, specialty, or any other provider attribute. It is a permanent, intelligence-free identifier.}

::Q-CRS-026:: Protected health information (PHI) includes any data that relates to a person's health condition, care received, or payment for care, and that can identify the individual. {TRUE #### PHI is defined as individually identifiable health information that relates to a person's health condition, care received, or payment for that care.}

::Q-CRS-027:: Under HIPAA, a covered entity must always obtain written patient authorization before sharing PHI for treatment purposes. {FALSE #### Under HIPAA, covered entities may share PHI without patient authorization for treatment, payment, and health care operations (TPO).}

::Q-CRS-028:: Under HIPAA, patients have the right to access and obtain copies of their own health records from a covered entity. {TRUE #### HIPAA gives patients the right to access and obtain copies of their health records from any covered entity within 30 days of request.}

::Q-CRS-029:: A clearinghouse sends claims directly to patients for review before forwarding them to the health plan. {FALSE #### A clearinghouse is an intermediary between providers and health plans. It converts transactions into HIPAA-standard formats and forwards them to the health plan — patients are not part of this process.}

::Q-CRS-030:: ASC X12 Version 5010 is the current HIPAA-adopted standard format for electronic healthcare transactions. {TRUE #### ASC X12 Version 5010 is the HIPAA-adopted standard used by providers, payors, and clearinghouses nationwide for electronic transactions.}

::Q-CRS-031:: HIPAA mandates standard electronic formats for claims submission but does not standardize eligibility verification or remittance advice transactions. {FALSE #### HIPAA's Administrative Simplification provisions standardize multiple transaction types including claims (837), remittance advice (835), eligibility verification (270/271), claim status (276/277), and referral authorization (278).}

::Q-CRS-032:: Providers can verify a patient's insurance eligibility before providing care by sending an electronic eligibility inquiry to the health plan. {TRUE #### Providers can send a HIPAA 270 transaction to the health plan before or at the time of service to verify coverage and benefits.}

::Q-CRS-033:: Each health plan requires a unique, plan-specific data format for electronic claims, making it impossible for one provider to submit to multiple plans using the same format. {FALSE #### Standardized transaction formats allow any provider to submit a claim to any health plan using the same data structure, enabling interoperability across the healthcare system.}

::Q-CRS-034:: An Explanation of Benefits (EOB) shows provider charges, allowed charges, the amount the insurer paid, and what the patient owes. {TRUE #### The EOB is a document sent by the health plan to the patient after a claim is processed, showing all of these amounts.}

::Q-CRS-035:: Who initiates a claim in the basic healthcare claims flow? {
~The patient submits the claim to the health plan #Patients do not typically submit claims; the provider handles claim submission.
=The provider submits the claim to the payor after delivering care #In the standard claims flow, the provider submits a claim to the payor after the patient receives care.
~The payor generates the claim automatically when care is delivered #Payors do not automatically generate claims; they receive and process claims submitted by providers.
~The clearinghouse creates the claim on behalf of the patient #Clearinghouses translate and forward claims but do not create them on behalf of patients.
}

::Q-CRS-036:: What method do providers primarily use to submit claims to payors under HIPAA? {
~Paper forms mailed through the postal service #While paper claims still exist in limited cases, HIPAA promotes and often requires electronic submission.
=Electronic submission using HIPAA-standard transaction formats #HIPAA requires providers to submit claims electronically using standard transaction formats.
~Verbal communication over the telephone #Claims are not submitted verbally.
~Faxed copies of the patient's medical record #Faxing medical records is not the standard method of claim submission under HIPAA.
}

::Q-CRS-037:: Which of the following is checked during the automated edits performed on an incoming claim? {
~The provider's personal credit score #A provider's credit score is not part of claim processing.
~Whether the patient has paid all previous medical bills #The patient's prior bill payment history is not checked during automated claim edits.
=Completeness of claim data, valid values, and duplicate submissions #Automated edits check for completeness, valid values, data consistency, duplicate submissions, and provider/beneficiary eligibility.
~Whether the patient's employer has approved the visit #Employer approval is not part of the automated claim edit process.
}

::Q-CRS-038:: What happens to a claim before it reaches the adjudication stage? {
~It is sent to the patient for approval #Patients do not approve claims before adjudication.
=It undergoes automated edits that check for completeness and eligibility #Before adjudication, automated edits verify completeness, valid values, data consistency, duplicate status, and beneficiary eligibility.
~It is published in a public database for transparency #Claims are not published in any public database.
~It is forwarded to a government agency for pre-approval #Claims are not routinely forwarded to a government agency for pre-approval.
}

::Q-CRS-039:: What does it mean when a healthcare claim is "rejected"? {
~The payor has determined the service is not covered under the patient's plan #This describes a denied claim, not a rejected one.
=The claim is returned to the provider for correction and may be resubmitted #A rejected claim is returned to the provider for correction, typically because of errors or missing information, and can be resubmitted.
~The patient must appeal the decision to a government agency #A rejected claim does not require a government appeal; it requires correction and resubmission.
~The provider must refund the patient in full #Rejection does not require a refund; the provider corrects and resubmits the claim.
}

::Q-CRS-040:: What is one reason a claim might be denied after adjudication? {
~The claim form was submitted using the correct HIPAA format #Using the correct format supports claim processing, not denial.
=The service is not covered under the patient's health plan #A claim may be denied if the service is not covered or does not meet policy requirements.
~The provider included a valid NPI on the claim #Including a valid NPI is required and would not cause a denial.
~The patient's eligibility was verified before the visit #Verified eligibility supports processing, not denial.
}

::Q-CRS-041:: When can a provider send an eligibility inquiry (270 transaction) to a health plan? {
~Only after the claim has been denied #Eligibility verification is typically done before or at the time of service, not only after a denial.
~Only during the annual open enrollment period #Eligibility inquiries can be sent at any time, not just during open enrollment.
=Before or at the time of service #Providers can verify eligibility before or at the time of service by sending a HIPAA 270 transaction to the health plan.
~Only after the patient has been discharged from the hospital #Checking eligibility after discharge would be too late for most purposes.
}

::Q-CRS-042:: What type of information is included in a real-time eligibility response from a health plan? {
~The provider's tax return information #Tax return information is not part of eligibility responses.
=Deductible, co-pay, and coinsurance details #Since 2013, HIPAA operating rules require real-time responses that include deductible, co-pay, and coinsurance information.
~A list of all claims the patient has ever filed #A full claims history is not returned in an eligibility response.
~The patient's complete medical history #Medical history is not part of an eligibility verification response.
}

::Q-CRS-043:: Why must every healthcare claim pair a diagnosis code with a procedure code? {
~To satisfy the provider's internal record-keeping requirements only #While codes appear in records, the pairing requirement is driven by billing and reimbursement, not just internal record-keeping.
=To link the clinical reason for care to the service performed, supporting the payor's reimbursement decision #The diagnosis code (ICD-10-CM) explains why care was needed, and the procedure code (CPT/HCPCS) describes the service performed; together they link clinical documentation to reimbursement.
~To allow the patient to choose their preferred treatment option #Code pairing is about billing, not patient treatment choice.
~To ensure the clearinghouse can assign an NPI to the claim #The clearinghouse does not assign NPIs based on code pairing.
}

::Q-CRS-044:: What happens when a provider submits a claim without a valid ICD-10-CM diagnosis code? {
~The payor processes the claim using a default diagnosis code #Payors do not assign default diagnosis codes to incomplete claims.
=The claim is returned to the provider as incomplete and will not be processed #A claim without a valid ICD-10-CM diagnosis code is returned as incomplete and will not be processed for payment.
~The clearinghouse assigns a diagnosis code automatically #Clearinghouses translate formats but do not add clinical codes to claims.
~The patient is contacted to provide the diagnosis information #Patients are not responsible for providing diagnosis codes.
}

::Q-CRS-045:: How do payors use the diagnosis code on a claim? {
~To assign the patient a primary care physician #Diagnosis codes are not used to assign physicians.
=To determine whether the procedure is medically necessary for the reported condition #Payors use the diagnosis code to determine medical necessity — whether the diagnosis supports the procedure according to coverage policy.
~To calculate the provider's annual income #Diagnosis codes do not relate to provider income calculations.
~To schedule the patient's next appointment #Scheduling is not a function of diagnosis codes on claims.
}

::Q-CRS-046:: Who receives the Explanation of Benefits (EOB)? {
~The clearinghouse #Clearinghouses do not receive EOBs.
~The provider's billing department #Providers receive the ERA (835), not the EOB. The EOB goes to the patient.
=The patient (or subscriber) #The EOB is sent by the health plan to the patient after a claim is processed.
~The employer's human resources department #EOBs go to the patient, not the employer.
}

::Q-CRS-047:: Which of the following pieces of information appears on an Explanation of Benefits (EOB)? {
~The provider's NPI application date #NPI application information does not appear on an EOB.
=The allowed charges and the amount the insurer paid #An EOB shows provider charges, allowed charges, the amount the insurer paid, and what the patient owes.
~The patient's complete prescription history #Prescription history is not included on an EOB for a specific claim.
~The clearinghouse's processing fee #Clearinghouse fees are not shown on a patient's EOB.
}

::Q-CRS-048:: Who sends the Electronic Remittance Advice (ERA) and who receives it? {
~The patient sends it to the provider #Patients are not involved in sending ERAs.
~The provider sends it to the payor #The provider submits claims, not ERAs. The ERA flows in the opposite direction.
=The payor sends it to the provider #After adjudication, the payor sends an ERA (HIPAA 835 transaction) to the provider detailing payment, adjustments, and denial reasons.
~The clearinghouse sends it to the patient #The ERA goes to the provider, not the patient.
}

::Q-CRS-049:: What information does an Electronic Remittance Advice (ERA) include? {
~The patient's treatment plan and medication list #Treatment plans and medication lists are clinical documents, not part of the ERA.
=Payment amount, adjustments, and reasons for any denials #The ERA details the payment amount, adjustments, and reasons for any denials after claim adjudication.
~The provider's malpractice insurance details #Malpractice insurance details are not included in an ERA.
~A referral to a specialist for follow-up care #Specialist referrals are not part of the ERA.
}

::Q-CRS-050:: What is the "allowed amount" in healthcare reimbursement? {
~The total charge the provider bills before insurance processing #The total billed charge is different from the allowed amount; the billed amount is often higher.
=The maximum amount a health plan will pay for a covered service #The allowed amount is the maximum the health plan will pay for a covered service. The provider may bill the patient for cost-sharing but generally not above the allowed amount for in-network services.
~The amount the patient pays as a monthly premium #Monthly premiums are separate from the allowed amount for individual services.
~The amount charged by the clearinghouse for processing the claim #Clearinghouse fees are not related to the allowed amount.
}

::Q-CRS-051:: After the health plan pays its share of the allowed amount, what may the patient still owe for an in-network service? {
~The full billed charge from the provider #For in-network services, the patient's responsibility is limited to cost-sharing within the allowed amount, not the full billed charge.
=Co-pay, coinsurance, or deductible amounts #The patient may owe cost-sharing amounts such as co-pay, coinsurance, or deductible, but not charges above the allowed amount for in-network services.
~The clearinghouse processing fee #Patients do not pay clearinghouse fees.
~A penalty for using an in-network provider #There is no penalty for using in-network providers; in fact, costs are typically lower in-network.
}

::Q-CRS-052:: What does a healthcare clearinghouse do with claims it receives from providers? {
~Diagnoses the patient's condition and updates the claim #Clearinghouses handle data formatting, not clinical diagnosis.
=Converts the claims into HIPAA-standard electronic formats and forwards them to the health plan #A clearinghouse receives claims from providers, converts them into HIPAA-standard formats, and forwards them to the appropriate health plan.
~Stores the claims permanently and does not forward them #Clearinghouses forward claims to health plans; they do not permanently hold them.
~Returns the claims to the patient for verification #Claims are forwarded to health plans, not returned to patients.
}

::Q-CRS-053:: Why might a provider use a clearinghouse instead of submitting claims directly to each health plan? {
~Clearinghouses provide medical care that the provider cannot #Clearinghouses do not provide medical care.
=Clearinghouses convert claims into the correct standard format for each plan, simplifying submission #Clearinghouses serve as intermediaries that translate and format claims into HIPAA-standard formats, making it easier for providers to submit to multiple health plans.
~Clearinghouses are required to approve all claims before payors can process them #Clearinghouses translate formats but do not approve claims.
~Clearinghouses eliminate the need for diagnosis and procedure codes #Clearinghouses do not remove the requirement for clinical codes.
}

::Q-CRS-054:: Which of the following are the three types of HIPAA covered entities? {
~Hospitals, pharmacies, and laboratories #These are specific types of providers, not the three covered entity categories.
=Health plans, health care providers who transmit transactions electronically, and clearinghouses #The three HIPAA covered entity types are health plans, health care providers who transmit transactions electronically, and clearinghouses.
~Medicare, Medicaid, and commercial insurers #These are types of health plans, not the three covered entity categories.
~Patients, employers, and government agencies #Patients, employers, and government agencies are not the three covered entity types under HIPAA.
}

::Q-CRS-055:: What does it mean that the NPI is "intelligence-free"? {
~It does not require a computer to look up #Intelligence-free describes the number carrying no embedded meaning, not whether a computer is needed to look it up.
=It carries no information about the provider's specialty, location, or type #The NPI is intelligence-free, meaning the number itself carries no information about the provider's location, specialty, or type — it is purely a unique identifier.
~It is automatically generated without human review #Intelligence-free refers to the number format carrying no provider information, not to how the number is reviewed or generated.
~It expires and must be renewed every 10 years #The NPI does not expire or require renewal; intelligence-free refers to the number carrying no embedded information.
}

::Q-CRS-056:: On which types of transactions must the NPI appear? {
~Only on paper claims #The NPI is required on electronic HIPAA transactions, not limited to paper claims.
~Only on claims for Medicare patients #The NPI is required for all HIPAA-covered transactions, not only Medicare.
=All electronic claims, eligibility inquiries, and other HIPAA transactions #The NPI must appear on all electronic claims, eligibility inquiries, and other HIPAA transactions.
~Only on transactions processed by clearinghouses #The NPI requirement applies to all HIPAA transactions, not just those routed through clearinghouses.
}

::Q-CRS-057:: What role does a healthcare clearinghouse play in the claims process? {
~It directly pays providers for services rendered #Clearinghouses do not pay providers; payors (health plans) are responsible for reimbursement.
=It converts non-standard claim data into standard HIPAA formats for submission to payors #A healthcare clearinghouse receives claims and other transactions from providers, converts them from non-standard formats into the standardized electronic formats required by HIPAA, and forwards them to the appropriate payor.
~It determines whether a patient is eligible for coverage #Eligibility determination is performed by the health plan, not the clearinghouse.
~It assigns diagnosis and procedure codes to patient encounters #Coding is performed by the provider or medical coder, not by the clearinghouse.
}

::Q-CRS-058:: Which of the following entities is NOT a HIPAA covered entity? {
~A commercial health insurance company #Health insurance companies are health plans and are covered entities under HIPAA.
~A hospital that submits claims electronically #Hospitals that transmit electronic transactions are covered entities.
~A healthcare clearinghouse #Clearinghouses are one of the three types of covered entities.
=A life insurance company that does not handle health information #HIPAA covered entities are health plans, health care providers who transmit transactions electronically, and clearinghouses. A life insurance company that does not handle health information is not a covered entity.
}

::Q-CRS-059:: Which of the following is an example of protected health information (PHI)? {
=A patient's name linked to their diagnosis in a medical record #PHI is any data relating to a person's health condition, care, or payment for care that can identify the individual — such as a name linked to a diagnosis.
~Aggregate hospital admission statistics with no individual identifiers #Aggregate data without individual identifiers is not PHI.
~A provider's office address published on their website #A provider's public business address is not PHI.
~The total revenue of a health plan reported in annual filings #A health plan's revenue figures are not individually identifiable health information.
}

::Q-CRS-060:: Under HIPAA, which set of purposes allows a covered entity to share PHI without patient authorization? {
~Marketing, fundraising, and research #Marketing and fundraising generally require patient authorization under HIPAA.
=Treatment, payment, and health care operations (TPO) #HIPAA allows covered entities to share PHI without patient authorization for treatment, payment, and health care operations (TPO).
~Employment, insurance underwriting, and law enforcement #These are not the TPO purposes recognized by HIPAA for sharing PHI without authorization.
~Education, media reporting, and public relations #Education and media reporting are not TPO purposes under HIPAA.
}

::Q-CRS-061:: What does HIPAA's minimum necessary standard require? {
~That covered entities use the minimum number of staff to handle PHI #The standard applies to information disclosed, not staffing levels.
=That PHI disclosures be limited to the smallest amount of information needed for the purpose #The minimum necessary standard requires covered entities to limit PHI use and disclosure to the smallest amount needed to accomplish the intended purpose.
~That patients provide the minimum amount of personal information at check-in #The standard governs how covered entities handle PHI, not what patients provide at check-in.
~That providers use the fewest possible procedure codes on a claim #The standard is about PHI disclosure, not the number of procedure codes on a claim.
}

::Q-CRS-062:: A hospital sends a patient's complete medical record to an insurance company that only requested lab results for a specific claim. Which HIPAA principle does this violate? {
~The right of access rule #The right of access applies to patients requesting their own records.
=The minimum necessary standard #Sending the complete medical record when only lab results were needed violates the minimum necessary standard, which requires limiting PHI to the smallest amount needed.
~The breach notification rule #The breach notification rule covers unauthorized disclosures; this is a minimum necessary violation.
~The TPO exception #TPO is a category of permitted uses, not a principle about limiting the amount of information shared.
}

::Q-CRS-063:: Within how many days must a covered entity provide a patient with copies of their health records after receiving a request? {
~7 days #The HIPAA requirement is 30 days, not 7.
~14 days #The HIPAA requirement is 30 days, not 14.
=30 days #Under HIPAA, covered entities must provide patients with access to their health records within 30 days of request.
~90 days #The HIPAA requirement is 30 days, not 90.
}

::Q-CRS-064:: Under HIPAA, patients have the right to do which of the following with their health records? {
~Delete any records they disagree with #Patients can request corrections, not unilateral deletions.
=Access their records and request corrections #Patients have the right under HIPAA to access and obtain copies of their health records and to request corrections.
~Sell their records to third-party researchers #HIPAA provides access rights, not the right to sell records.
~Prevent their provider from documenting any care #Patients cannot prevent providers from maintaining required clinical documentation.
}

::Q-CRS-065:: Which HIPAA standard transaction is used for claims submission? {
~835 #The 835 is the remittance advice (payment) transaction.
=837 #The 837 transaction is the HIPAA standard for electronic claims submission.
~270 #The 270 is the eligibility inquiry transaction.
~278 #The 278 is the referral authorization transaction.
}

::Q-CRS-066:: Which HIPAA standard transaction is used for remittance advice (payment details)? {
~837 #The 837 is used for claims submission, not remittance advice.
~270 #The 270 is used for eligibility inquiries.
=835 #The 835 transaction is the HIPAA standard for electronic remittance advice, which details payment information from the payor to the provider.
~276 #The 276 is used for claim status inquiries.
}

::Q-CRS-067:: Which pair of HIPAA transactions covers eligibility verification? {
~837 and 835 #The 837 is for claims submission and the 835 is for remittance advice.
=270 and 271 #The 270 transaction is the eligibility inquiry, and the 271 is the eligibility response.
~276 and 277 #The 276/277 pair covers claim status inquiries and responses.
~278 and 279 #The 278 is for referral authorization; there is no standard 279 transaction.
}

::Q-CRS-068:: Which HIPAA transaction pair is used for claim status inquiries and responses? {
~270 and 271 #The 270/271 pair is used for eligibility verification, not claim status.
~837 and 835 #The 837 is for claims submission and the 835 is for remittance advice.
=276 and 277 #The 276 transaction is the claim status inquiry, and the 277 is the claim status response.
~278 and 835 #The 278 is for referral authorization, and the 835 is for remittance advice; they are not a paired transaction.
}

::Q-CRS-069:: What is the HIPAA 278 transaction used for? {
~Claims submission #Claims submission uses the 837 transaction.
~Remittance advice #Remittance advice uses the 835 transaction.
=Referral authorization #The 278 transaction is the HIPAA standard for referral authorization requests and responses.
~Eligibility verification #Eligibility verification uses the 270/271 transaction pair.
}

::Q-CRS-070:: Which organizations use the ASC X12 Version 5010 standard? {
~Only Medicare and Medicaid #The standard applies to all HIPAA-covered entities, not just Medicare and Medicaid.
=Providers, payors, and clearinghouses nationwide #ASC X12 Version 5010 is used by providers, payors, and clearinghouses nationwide as the HIPAA-adopted standard for electronic transactions.
~Only hospitals with more than 100 beds #The standard applies to all covered providers, regardless of size.
~Only clearinghouses that process government claims #All clearinghouses use this standard, not just those processing government claims.
}

::Q-CRS-071:: What is the primary benefit of standardized electronic transaction formats in healthcare? {
~They allow patients to submit their own claims directly to the government #Patients typically do not submit claims; providers do.
=They enable any provider to submit a claim to any health plan using the same data structure #Standardized formats enable interoperability — any provider can communicate with any health plan using the same data structure.
~They eliminate the need for diagnosis and procedure codes #Standardized formats still require diagnosis and procedure codes.
~They allow payors to set their own unique claim formats #The purpose of standardization is a common format, not plan-specific ones.
}

::Q-CRS-072:: In the basic claims flow, what is the payor's role? {
~To deliver care to the patient #Delivering care is the provider's role.
~To convert claims into standard formats #Converting claims to standard formats is the clearinghouse's role.
=To process the claim and issue payment to the provider #In the claims flow, the payor (health plan) receives the claim, processes it through adjudication, and issues payment.
~To schedule the patient's appointment #Scheduling appointments is not the payor's role in the claims flow.
}

::Q-CRS-073:: Which coding system is used for diagnosis codes on a healthcare claim? {
~CPT #CPT codes describe procedures and services, not diagnoses.
~HCPCS Level II #HCPCS Level II codes describe supplies and services, not diagnoses.
=ICD-10-CM #ICD-10-CM is the coding system used for diagnosis codes, describing the clinical reason care was needed.
~ASC X12 #ASC X12 is a transaction standard format, not a coding system for diagnoses.
}

::Q-CRS-074:: Which coding systems are used for procedure codes on healthcare claims? {
~ICD-10-CM and ICD-10-PCS only #ICD-10-PCS is used for inpatient procedure coding; CPT and HCPCS are the standard procedure code sets on claims.
=CPT and HCPCS #CPT and HCPCS codes describe the procedures and services performed, and are paired with ICD-10-CM diagnosis codes on claims.
~NPI and EIN #NPI is a provider identifier and EIN is a tax number; neither is a procedure code system.
~837 and 835 #These are HIPAA transaction numbers, not coding systems.
}

::Q-CRS-075:: If a provider submits a claim with a diagnosis code that does not support the procedure code according to the payor's coverage policy, what is the likely result? {
~The claim is approved at a higher rate #A mismatched diagnosis-procedure pair would not increase payment.
=The claim may be denied for lack of medical necessity #If the diagnosis does not support the procedure according to coverage policy, the payor may deny the claim for lack of medical necessity.
~The payor automatically changes the diagnosis code #Payors do not automatically change diagnosis codes submitted by providers.
~The clearinghouse removes the procedure code before forwarding #Clearinghouses do not alter clinical codes on claims.
}

::Q-CRS-076:: Why is it important for patients to understand that an EOB is not a bill? {
=Because the EOB shows more than the patient owes — it includes how the plan processed the entire claim #An EOB is a summary of how the plan processed the claim, showing charges, allowed amounts, plan payments, and patient responsibility. Patients should compare it to the actual bill from the provider.
~Because the EOB requires immediate payment to the health plan #The EOB does not require payment to the health plan; the patient pays the provider.
~Because the EOB replaces the provider's bill entirely #The EOB does not replace the provider's bill; patients should compare both documents.
~Because the EOB can be used as a tax deduction receipt #An EOB is not designed as a tax receipt.
}

::Q-CRS-077:: What changed about eligibility verification on January 1, 2013? {
~Eligibility verification was no longer required for Medicare patients #Eligibility verification is still required for Medicare.
=HIPAA operating rules began requiring health plans to respond to eligibility inquiries in real time #HIPAA operating rules effective January 1, 2013, require health plans to respond to eligibility inquiries in real time, including deductible, co-pay, and coinsurance information.
~Providers were no longer allowed to verify eligibility before providing care #Providers are still permitted and encouraged to verify eligibility before providing care.
~The 270 transaction was replaced by a new standard #The 270 transaction is still the standard for eligibility inquiries.
}

::Q-CRS-078:: A healthcare clearinghouse handles PHI when processing claims. Under HIPAA, what obligation does this create? {
~The clearinghouse must delete all PHI within 24 hours #There is no 24-hour deletion requirement; the obligation is to protect PHI.
=The clearinghouse must protect PHI as a HIPAA covered entity #Clearinghouses are one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities and must protect PHI under the Privacy Rule.
~The clearinghouse is exempt from HIPAA because it does not provide care #Clearinghouses are explicitly included as HIPAA covered entities.
~The clearinghouse must obtain patient authorization before forwarding each claim #Clearinghouses process claims under TPO and do not need individual patient authorization for each claim.
}

::Q-CRS-079:: A provider shares a patient's lab results with a specialist to coordinate treatment. Does this require the patient's written authorization under HIPAA? {
~Yes, written authorization is always required before sharing any PHI #HIPAA does not require written authorization for TPO purposes.
=No, sharing PHI for treatment is permitted under the TPO exception without patient authorization #Under HIPAA, covered entities may share PHI for treatment, payment, and health care operations (TPO) without patient authorization. Coordinating care with a specialist falls under treatment.
~Yes, but only if the specialist is out of network #The TPO exception applies regardless of network status.
~No, because lab results are not considered PHI #Lab results linked to a patient are PHI.
}

::Q-CRS-080:: HIPAA's Administrative Simplification provisions mandate standard formats for which of the following? {
~Only claims submission (837) #The provisions cover multiple transaction types, not just claims submission.
=Claims (837), remittance (835), eligibility (270/271), claim status (276/277), and referral authorization (278) #HIPAA's Administrative Simplification provisions mandate standard electronic formats for all of these key transaction types.
~Only eligibility verification (270/271) and remittance advice (835) #The provisions cover more than just eligibility and remittance transactions.
~Only transactions between government programs like Medicare and Medicaid #The standards apply to all HIPAA-covered entities, not just government programs.
}


$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Healthcare Data

::Q-DAT-001:: Protected Health Information (PHI) is only protected under HIPAA when it is stored electronically. {FALSE #### PHI is protected under HIPAA regardless of its form — electronic, paper, or oral.}

::Q-DAT-002:: The minimum necessary standard applies to disclosures of PHI for treatment purposes between health care providers. {FALSE #### Disclosures of PHI for treatment purposes between health care providers are exempt from the minimum necessary requirement.}

::Q-DAT-003:: A business associate must sign a written agreement to comply with HIPAA rules before handling PHI on behalf of a covered entity. {TRUE #### A business associate is required to sign a written agreement (Business Associate Agreement) to comply with HIPAA rules before handling PHI on behalf of a covered entity.}

::Q-DAT-004:: The United States transitioned from ICD-9 to ICD-10 on October 1, 2015. {TRUE #### The U.S. transitioned from ICD-9 to ICD-10 on October 1, 2015, expanding from approximately 14,000 diagnosis codes to approximately 69,000.}

::Q-DAT-005:: An in-network provider has a contract with the patient's health insurer to provide services at pre-negotiated rates. {TRUE #### An in-network provider has a contract with the patient's health insurer to provide services at pre-negotiated rates, which results in lower out-of-pocket costs for the patient.}

::Q-DAT-006:: Which of the following best defines Protected Health Information (PHI)? {
~Any medical data stored in a hospital's computer system #Not all data in a hospital computer is PHI; it must be individually identifiable and related to health, care, or payment.
=Individually identifiable health information relating to a person's health, care, or payment for care #PHI is individually identifiable health information that relates to a person's past, present, or future physical or mental health, the provision of health care, or payment for health care.
~A patient's name and address regardless of whether it is linked to health data #A name and address alone, without a link to health information, is not PHI.
~Only electronic records that contain diagnosis codes #PHI is not limited to electronic records or diagnosis codes; it covers all forms and types of health information.
}

::Q-DAT-007:: Which of the following is an example of a common identifier included in PHI? {
~A patient's favorite color #A favorite color is not a health identifier and is not part of PHI.
=A patient's Social Security Number linked to health information #PHI includes common identifiers such as a patient's name, address, date of birth, and Social Security Number when they are associated with health information.
~The brand of medical equipment used during treatment #An equipment brand name does not identify an individual patient.
~The name of the hospital's CEO #The hospital CEO's name is not individually identifiable health information about a patient.
}

::Q-DAT-008:: What does the HIPAA Privacy Rule establish? {
~Technical standards for encrypting electronic health records #Technical standards for electronic data are addressed by the HIPAA Security Rule, not the Privacy Rule.
=National standards for protecting individually identifiable health information #The HIPAA Privacy Rule establishes national standards for protecting individually identifiable health information held or transmitted by covered entities and their business associates.
~Reimbursement rates for Medicare claims #Reimbursement rates are set by CMS fee schedules, not by the Privacy Rule.
~Licensing requirements for health care providers #Provider licensing is governed by state agencies, not the Privacy Rule.
}

::Q-DAT-009:: What does the minimum necessary standard require covered entities to do? {
~Share all available PHI to ensure thorough treatment #Sharing all available PHI contradicts the minimum necessary standard; only the needed information should be shared.
=Limit the use and disclosure of PHI to the minimum amount needed for the intended purpose #The minimum necessary standard requires covered entities to make reasonable efforts to limit the use and disclosure of PHI to the minimum amount needed to accomplish the intended purpose.
~Store the minimum number of patient records required by law #The standard relates to limiting disclosures, not to the number of records stored.
~Require patients to provide the minimum amount of personal information #The standard applies to how covered entities handle PHI, not to what patients provide.
}

::Q-DAT-010:: Which of the following is NOT one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities? {
~Health plans #Health plans are one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities.
~Health care clearinghouses #Health care clearinghouses are one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities.
=Pharmaceutical manufacturers #HIPAA defines three types of covered entities: health plans, health care clearinghouses, and health care providers who transmit health information electronically. Pharmaceutical manufacturers are not covered entities.
~Health care providers who transmit health information electronically #Health care providers who transmit health information electronically are one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities.
}

::Q-DAT-011:: Which three categories of safeguards does the HIPAA Security Rule require? {
=Administrative, physical, and technical #The HIPAA Security Rule requires three categories of safeguards: administrative (policies and procedures), physical (protection of facilities and equipment), and technical (technology controls for access and data protection).
~Clinical, financial, and operational #Clinical, financial, and operational are not the safeguard categories defined by the Security Rule.
~Federal, state, and local #Federal, state, and local refer to levels of government, not Security Rule safeguard categories.
~Preventive, detective, and corrective #Preventive, detective, and corrective are general security control types but not the categories specified in the HIPAA Security Rule.
}

::Q-DAT-012:: Under the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule, within how many days must a covered entity notify affected individuals of a breach of unsecured PHI? {
~30 days #30 days is the timeframe for responding to a patient's access request, not for breach notification.
=60 days #The Breach Notification Rule requires covered entities to notify affected individuals without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 days after discovering the breach.
~90 days #90 days exceeds the maximum allowed notification period for a breach.
~120 days #120 days exceeds the maximum allowed notification period for a breach.
}

::Q-DAT-013:: Which coding system is used to classify medical diagnoses? {
~CPT #CPT codes identify medical services and procedures performed by providers, not diagnoses.
=ICD #ICD (International Classification of Diseases) codes are standardized codes used to represent medical diagnoses and inpatient procedures on claims and medical records.
~HCPCS Level II #HCPCS Level II codes cover products, supplies, and services such as ambulance services and DME.
~NPI #NPI is a provider identification number, not a coding system for diagnoses.
}

::Q-DAT-014:: What type of codes are CPT codes, and who maintains them? {
~Diagnosis codes maintained by the World Health Organization #ICD codes, not CPT codes, classify diagnoses. The World Health Organization maintains ICD internationally.
~Supply codes maintained by CMS #CMS maintains HCPCS Level II codes for supplies and equipment, not CPT codes.
=5-digit procedure codes maintained by the American Medical Association (AMA) #CPT (Current Procedural Terminology) codes are 5-digit numeric codes maintained by the American Medical Association (AMA) that identify medical services and procedures.
~7-character condition codes maintained by HHS #ICD-10 codes can be up to 7 characters; CPT codes are 5-digit numeric codes maintained by the AMA.
}

::Q-DAT-015:: What is an Electronic Health Record (EHR)? {
~A paper chart stored in a filing cabinet at the provider's office #A paper chart is a traditional medical record, not an electronic health record.
=A digital version of a patient's medical history maintained by the provider over time #An EHR is a digital version of a patient's medical history maintained by the provider over time, including demographics, medications, vital signs, immunizations, lab results, and radiology reports.
~An insurance claim submitted electronically to a health plan #An electronic claim is a billing transaction, not an EHR.
~A billing statement sent to the patient after a visit #A billing statement is a financial document, not a comprehensive digital medical record.
}

::Q-DAT-016:: PHI includes information about a person's past, present, or future physical or mental health condition. {TRUE #### By definition, PHI covers individually identifiable health information relating to past, present, or future health, care, or payment for care.}

::Q-DAT-017:: A patient's date of birth becomes PHI only when it is linked to health information. {TRUE #### Common identifiers such as date of birth become PHI when they are associated with health information about the individual.}

::Q-DAT-018:: A conversation between a doctor and a nurse about a patient's diagnosis is not considered PHI because it is spoken aloud. {FALSE #### PHI is protected under HIPAA regardless of form, including oral communications.}

::Q-DAT-019:: Under the HIPAA Privacy Rule, patients have the right to obtain a copy of their own protected health information. {TRUE #### The HIPAA Privacy Rule gives individuals the right to access, inspect, and obtain a copy of their own PHI.}

::Q-DAT-020:: A health care clearinghouse is one of the three types of HIPAA covered entities. {TRUE #### HIPAA defines three types of covered entities — health plans, health care clearinghouses, and certain health care providers.}

::Q-DAT-021:: The HIPAA Security Rule applies to all forms of PHI, including paper records and oral communications. {FALSE #### The HIPAA Security Rule specifically protects electronic PHI (ePHI). The Privacy Rule, not the Security Rule, covers PHI in all forms.}

::Q-DAT-022:: Physical safeguards under the HIPAA Security Rule include policies for protecting facilities and equipment that store ePHI. {TRUE #### Physical safeguards address the protection of physical facilities, workstations, and devices that store or access ePHI.}

::Q-DAT-023:: When a breach of unsecured PHI affects 500 or more residents of a state, the covered entity must notify prominent media outlets. {TRUE #### The Breach Notification Rule requires media notification when a breach affects 500 or more residents of a state or jurisdiction.}

::Q-DAT-024:: Breaches of unsecured PHI that affect fewer than 500 individuals do not need to be reported to HHS at all. {FALSE #### Smaller breaches (fewer than 500 individuals) must still be reported to HHS, but they are submitted annually rather than within 60 days.}

::Q-DAT-025:: ICD-10-PCS codes are used by all health care providers in every clinical setting to code diagnoses. {FALSE #### ICD-10-PCS codes are used specifically for inpatient hospital procedures. ICD-10-CM codes are used by all providers to code diagnoses.}

::Q-DAT-026:: ICD-10 codes can be up to 7 characters long, providing more clinical detail than ICD-9 codes. {TRUE #### ICD-10 codes can be up to 7 characters, compared to shorter ICD-9 codes, allowing more detail about location, severity, and type of condition.}

::Q-DAT-027:: CPT codes are maintained by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS). {FALSE #### CPT codes are maintained by the American Medical Association (AMA), not CMS. HCPCS Level II codes are maintained by CMS.}

::Q-DAT-028:: Patients typically pay less when they receive care from an out-of-network provider compared to an in-network provider. {FALSE #### Out-of-network providers do not have pre-negotiated rates with the insurer, so patients typically pay significantly more.}

::Q-DAT-029:: One benefit of Electronic Health Records is reducing the duplication of tests for patients. {TRUE #### EHRs help reduce duplication of tests by making health information available electronically to authorized providers.}

::Q-DAT-030:: HCPCS Level II codes are the same as CPT codes. {FALSE #### HCPCS Level I consists of CPT codes, not Level II. Level II covers products, supplies, and services not included in CPT.}

::Q-DAT-031:: A business associate may handle PHI on behalf of a covered entity without any written agreement as long as both parties verbally agree. {FALSE #### A business associate must sign a written Business Associate Agreement before handling PHI on behalf of a covered entity.}

::Q-DAT-032:: The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to ensure the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of ePHI. {TRUE #### The Security Rule establishes national standards to protect ePHI, requiring confidentiality, integrity, and availability.}

::Q-DAT-033:: Certified EHR technology stores patient data in an unstructured format that requires manual sorting by providers. {FALSE #### Certified EHR technology stores patient data in a structured format that allows easy retrieval, transfer, and use.}

::Q-DAT-034:: The transition from ICD-9 to ICD-10 expanded the number of available diagnosis codes from approximately 14,000 to approximately 69,000. {TRUE #### The ICD-10 transition dramatically increased the number of available diagnosis codes from roughly 14,000 to roughly 69,000.}

::Q-DAT-035:: Which of the following categories of information does PHI relate to? {
=A person's health condition, health care provision, or payment for health care #PHI relates to a person's past, present, or future health, the provision of health care, or payment for health care.
~A person's employment history and salary information #Employment and salary data are not health information and are not covered by HIPAA.
~A person's educational background and academic records #Educational records fall under FERPA, not HIPAA.
~A person's criminal record and court proceedings #Criminal records are not health information protected under HIPAA.
}

::Q-DAT-036:: Which of the following is NOT typically considered a common PHI identifier? {
~Patient's name #A patient's name linked to health information is a common PHI identifier.
=Patient's blood type when not linked to any identifying information #A blood type by itself, with no link to an individual's identity, is not PHI. PHI requires both health data and an identifier.
~Patient's Social Security Number linked to health data #A Social Security Number linked to health data is a classic example of PHI.
~Patient's home address linked to health data #A home address linked to health information qualifies as PHI.
}

::Q-DAT-037:: PHI is protected under HIPAA in which of the following forms? {
~Electronic only #Electronic-only protection would leave paper records and spoken information unprotected.
~Electronic and paper only #Oral communications containing PHI are also protected under HIPAA.
=Electronic, paper, and oral #HIPAA protects PHI regardless of its form — electronic, paper, or oral.
~Paper and oral only #Electronic PHI is also protected under HIPAA, particularly by the Security Rule.
}

::Q-DAT-038:: The HIPAA Privacy Rule applies to which of the following? {
~Only hospitals and physician offices #The Privacy Rule applies to all covered entities, not just hospitals and physician offices.
=Covered entities and their business associates #The Privacy Rule establishes standards for covered entities and their business associates regarding the protection of PHI.
~Only health insurance companies #Health plans are only one type of covered entity. Providers and clearinghouses are also covered.
~Only federal government health programs #The Privacy Rule applies broadly to covered entities in both the private and public sectors.
}

::Q-DAT-039:: What is the purpose of the minimum necessary standard? {
~To require the smallest possible electronic file size for health records #The standard relates to PHI disclosure limits, not file size or data storage.
=To limit PHI use and disclosure to the minimum amount needed for the intended purpose #The minimum necessary standard requires covered entities to limit PHI use and disclosure to the minimum needed for the intended purpose.
~To ensure that only the minimum number of staff members have access to medical equipment #Staffing levels for equipment access are not related to the minimum necessary standard.
~To set the minimum number of patient visits required before PHI can be created #The standard governs how much PHI is shared, not how many patient visits occur.
}

::Q-DAT-040:: Which type of PHI disclosure is exempt from the minimum necessary requirement? {
~Disclosures for health plan marketing campaigns #Marketing disclosures are not exempt from HIPAA requirements.
=Disclosures for treatment purposes between health care providers #Treatment-related disclosures between health care providers are specifically exempt from the minimum necessary standard.
~Disclosures to law enforcement for non-urgent inquiries #Law enforcement disclosures are not broadly exempt from the minimum necessary standard.
~Disclosures to employers for workplace wellness programs #Employer wellness disclosures are not exempt from the minimum necessary requirement.
}

::Q-DAT-041:: Under the HIPAA Privacy Rule, which right do patients have regarding their PHI? {
~The right to delete any information from the provider's records permanently #Patients can request amendments, but providers are not required to delete records.
=The right to access, inspect, and obtain a copy of their PHI #The Privacy Rule grants individuals the right to access, inspect, and obtain a copy of their own PHI.
~The right to prevent any provider from viewing their PHI #Patients cannot universally block all provider access to PHI needed for treatment.
~The right to edit their medical records directly without provider involvement #Patients may request amendments, but they cannot directly edit their medical records.
}

::Q-DAT-042:: Which of the following qualifies as a HIPAA covered entity? {
=A health care provider who transmits health information electronically in connection with covered transactions #Health care providers who transmit health information electronically in connection with covered transactions are one of the three types of covered entities.
~A medical device manufacturer that sells equipment to hospitals #Medical device manufacturers are not covered entities unless they also function as a provider, plan, or clearinghouse.
~A pharmaceutical company that develops prescription drugs #Pharmaceutical companies are not covered entities under HIPAA.
~A health and wellness blog that publishes medical advice #A blog publishing medical advice is not a covered entity.
}

::Q-DAT-043:: What distinguishes a health care clearinghouse from other covered entities? {
~It provides direct patient care in a clinical setting #Clearinghouses do not provide direct patient care — that is the role of providers.
=It processes health information received from another entity into a standard format #Health care clearinghouses process health information received from one entity into a standard format for another entity.
~It sells health insurance policies to individuals #Selling insurance policies is the function of health plans, not clearinghouses.
~It manufactures medical equipment for hospitals #Equipment manufacturing is not a clearinghouse function.
}

::Q-DAT-044:: What must a business associate sign before handling PHI on behalf of a covered entity? {
~A patient consent form #Patient consent forms are signed by patients, not business associates.
=A written Business Associate Agreement #A business associate must sign a written Business Associate Agreement (BAA) to comply with HIPAA rules before handling PHI.
~A state medical license application #A medical license is for health care providers, not business associates.
~A provider enrollment form #Provider enrollment is for providers participating in health plans, not for business associates.
}

::Q-DAT-045:: Which of the following is an example of a business associate? {
~A patient receiving treatment at a hospital #A patient is not a business associate — they are the individual whose PHI is being protected.
=A billing company that processes claims containing PHI for a physician's office #A billing company that handles PHI on behalf of a covered entity is a business associate and must have a BAA in place.
~A nurse providing direct care to a patient in a hospital #A nurse providing care is part of the covered entity (the provider), not a separate business associate.
~A health insurer paying claims to a provider #A health insurer is itself a covered entity, not a business associate of another covered entity in this context.
}

::Q-DAT-046:: The HIPAA Security Rule specifically protects which type of information? {
~All patient information in any form #The Security Rule focuses on ePHI. The Privacy Rule provides broader protection for PHI in all forms.
=Electronic protected health information (ePHI) #The Security Rule specifically addresses the protection of electronic protected health information (ePHI).
~Only paper-based medical records #Paper records are covered by the Privacy Rule, not the Security Rule.
~Only oral communications between providers #Oral communications are covered by the Privacy Rule, not the Security Rule.
}

::Q-DAT-047:: Which of the following is one of the three core objectives the HIPAA Security Rule aims to ensure for ePHI? {
~Profitability #Profitability is a business objective, not a security objective under HIPAA.
=Availability #The Security Rule requires ensuring the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of ePHI.
~Portability #While HIPAA includes portability provisions, the Security Rule focuses on confidentiality, integrity, and availability.
~Marketability #Marketability is not a security objective under HIPAA.
}

::Q-DAT-048:: Which of the following is an example of an administrative safeguard under the HIPAA Security Rule? {
~Installing locks on server room doors #Locks on server rooms are a physical safeguard.
=Implementing workforce training policies on handling ePHI #Administrative safeguards include policies and procedures such as workforce training on handling ePHI.
~Using encryption software to protect data in transit #Encryption is a technical safeguard.
~Placing fire extinguishers near data storage equipment #Fire protection for equipment is a physical safeguard.
}

::Q-DAT-049:: Which of the following is an example of a technical safeguard under the HIPAA Security Rule? {
~Conducting background checks on employees #Background checks are an administrative safeguard.
~Storing backup tapes in a locked offsite location #Offsite storage of backup tapes is a physical safeguard.
=Implementing access controls that require unique user IDs and passwords #Technical safeguards are technology-based controls such as access controls, user authentication, and encryption.
~Training staff on privacy policies #Staff training is an administrative safeguard.
}

::Q-DAT-050:: Under the Breach Notification Rule, what is the maximum number of days a covered entity has to notify affected individuals after discovering a breach of unsecured PHI? {
~30 days #30 days is shorter than the required notification window.
~45 days #45 days is not the correct timeframe under the rule.
=60 days #The Breach Notification Rule requires notification without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 days after discovery.
~90 days #90 days exceeds the maximum allowed notification period.
}

::Q-DAT-051:: What triggers the requirement for a covered entity to notify prominent media outlets about a breach? {
~Any breach affecting at least one individual #Media notification is not required for every breach — only large-scale breaches trigger this requirement.
=A breach affecting 500 or more residents of a state or jurisdiction #Media notification is required when a breach affects 500 or more residents of a single state or jurisdiction.
~A breach involving electronic records only #The format of the records is not what triggers media notification — it is the number of affected individuals.
~A breach that occurs at a federal government facility #The type of facility does not determine whether media notification is required.
}

::Q-DAT-052:: How are breaches of unsecured PHI affecting fewer than 500 individuals reported to HHS? {
~They do not need to be reported to HHS #All breaches of unsecured PHI must be reported to HHS regardless of size.
~They must be reported within 60 days of discovery #The 60-day individual notification requirement applies, but HHS reporting for small breaches is annual.
=They are submitted to HHS annually #Smaller breaches affecting fewer than 500 individuals are reported to HHS on an annual basis.
~They are reported to state authorities instead of HHS #HHS reporting is required for all breaches. State notification may also apply but does not replace HHS reporting.
}

::Q-DAT-053:: What does the abbreviation ICD stand for? {
~Integrated Clinical Database #There is no standardized coding system called the Integrated Clinical Database.
=International Classification of Diseases #ICD stands for International Classification of Diseases, the standardized system for coding diagnoses.
~Internal Code for Diagnoses #ICD does not stand for Internal Code for Diagnoses.
~Insurance Claims Documentation #ICD is a diagnostic classification system, not an insurance claims documentation system.
}

::Q-DAT-054:: ICD codes are primarily used to represent which of the following on claims and medical records? {
~Provider credentials and specialties #Provider credentials are not represented by ICD codes.
=Medical diagnoses and inpatient procedures #ICD codes are standardized codes used to represent medical diagnoses and inpatient procedures on claims and records.
~Insurance premium amounts #Insurance premiums are financial amounts, not coded with ICD.
~Prescription drug dosages #Drug dosages are not classified using ICD codes.
}

::Q-DAT-055:: On what date did the United States transition from ICD-9 to ICD-10? {
~January 1, 2010 #January 1, 2010 was not the ICD-10 transition date.
=October 1, 2015 #The U.S. transitioned from ICD-9 to ICD-10 on October 1, 2015.
~July 1, 2013 #July 1, 2013 was not the transition date, though it was an earlier proposed deadline.
~March 1, 2018 #March 1, 2018 is well after the actual transition date.
}

::Q-DAT-056:: Approximately how many diagnosis codes does ICD-10 contain, compared to ICD-9? {
~ICD-9 had 69,000; ICD-10 has 14,000 #This reverses the numbers. ICD-10 has more codes than ICD-9.
=ICD-9 had 14,000; ICD-10 has 69,000 #ICD-9 had approximately 14,000 diagnosis codes; ICD-10 expanded this to approximately 69,000.
~ICD-9 had 5,000; ICD-10 has 25,000 #These numbers do not reflect the actual code counts for either system.
~ICD-9 had 30,000; ICD-10 has 100,000 #Neither 30,000 nor 100,000 reflects the actual code counts.
}

::Q-DAT-057:: Which coding system is used specifically for inpatient hospital procedures? {
~ICD-10-CM #ICD-10-CM is used for diagnosis coding across all settings, not specifically for inpatient procedures.
=ICD-10-PCS #ICD-10-PCS (Procedure Coding System) is used specifically for coding inpatient hospital procedures.
~CPT #CPT codes identify medical services and procedures but are not specific to inpatient hospital procedures.
~HCPCS Level II #HCPCS Level II codes cover supplies, equipment, and services not included in CPT.
}

::Q-DAT-058:: What does the abbreviation CM stand for in ICD-10-CM? {
~Comprehensive Medicine #CM does not stand for Comprehensive Medicine.
=Clinical Modification #CM stands for Clinical Modification. ICD-10-CM codes are used by all providers to code diagnoses.
~Claims Management #CM does not stand for Claims Management.
~Certified Medical #CM does not stand for Certified Medical.
}

::Q-DAT-059:: What is the maximum character length of an ICD-10 code? {
~3 characters #3 characters would be the minimum category code, not the maximum length.
~5 characters #5 characters is the length of CPT codes, not the maximum for ICD-10.
=7 characters #ICD-10 codes can be up to 7 characters long, providing detail about location, severity, and type of condition.
~10 characters #ICD-10 codes do not extend to 10 characters.
}

::Q-DAT-060:: What advantage does the longer character length of ICD-10 codes provide over ICD-9? {
~Faster claims processing speed #Code length does not directly determine claims processing speed.
=More detail about the location, severity, and type of a condition #The expanded character length of ICD-10 allows more clinical detail about location, severity, and type of condition.
~Lower insurance premiums for patients #Insurance premiums are not determined by the length of diagnosis codes.
~Fewer codes for providers to memorize #ICD-10 actually has far more codes than ICD-9, not fewer.
}

::Q-DAT-061:: HCPCS is a standardized coding system with how many levels? {
~One #HCPCS has two levels, not one.
=Two #HCPCS has two levels — Level I (CPT codes) and Level II (products, supplies, and services not included in CPT).
~Three #HCPCS has two levels. There was historically a Level III, but it was discontinued.
~Four #HCPCS does not have four levels.
}

::Q-DAT-062:: What does HCPCS Level II cover that is not included in CPT? {
~Surgical procedures performed in hospitals #Surgical procedures are typically coded using CPT or ICD-10-PCS, not HCPCS Level II.
=Products, supplies, and services such as ambulance rides and durable medical equipment #HCPCS Level II covers products, supplies, and services not included in CPT, such as ambulance services and durable medical equipment.
~Mental health diagnosis codes #Mental health diagnoses are coded with ICD codes, not HCPCS Level II.
~Laboratory test result interpretations #Lab test interpretations are typically coded with CPT, not HCPCS Level II.
}

::Q-DAT-063:: How many digits does a CPT code contain? {
~3 digits #CPT codes are longer than 3 digits.
~4 digits #4 digits is the numeric portion of a HCPCS Level II code, but CPT codes have 5 digits.
=5 digits #CPT codes are 5-digit numeric codes that identify medical services and procedures.
~7 digits #7 characters is the maximum length for ICD-10 codes, not CPT.
}

::Q-DAT-064:: What organization maintains and publishes CPT codes? {
~Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) #CMS maintains HCPCS Level II codes, not CPT codes.
~World Health Organization (WHO) #WHO maintains the ICD classification system, not CPT.
=American Medical Association (AMA) #The American Medical Association (AMA) develops and maintains CPT codes.
~Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) #HHS oversees HIPAA enforcement but does not maintain CPT codes.
}

::Q-DAT-065:: What is the format of a HCPCS Level II code? {
~5 numeric digits #5 numeric digits describes a CPT code, not a HCPCS Level II code.
=One alphabetical letter followed by 4 numeric digits #HCPCS Level II codes consist of one alphabetical letter followed by 4 numeric digits.
~7 alphanumeric characters #7 alphanumeric characters describes the maximum length of an ICD-10 code.
~Two letters followed by 3 numeric digits #HCPCS Level II codes begin with one letter, not two.
}

::Q-DAT-066:: Who maintains HCPCS Level II codes? {
~The American Medical Association (AMA) #The AMA maintains CPT codes (HCPCS Level I), not Level II.
~The World Health Organization (WHO) #WHO maintains the ICD system, not HCPCS Level II.
=The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) #CMS maintains HCPCS Level II codes to identify items such as ambulance services, durable medical equipment, and prosthetics.
~The American Hospital Association (AHA) #The AHA is not responsible for maintaining HCPCS Level II codes.
}

::Q-DAT-067:: Which of the following items would most likely be coded using a HCPCS Level II code? {
~An office visit with a primary care physician #An office visit would typically be coded with a CPT code.
=A wheelchair provided to a patient as durable medical equipment #HCPCS Level II codes identify items like durable medical equipment, ambulance services, and prosthetics.
~A diagnosis of type 2 diabetes #A diagnosis is coded using an ICD code, not HCPCS Level II.
~An outpatient knee surgery #Outpatient surgery is typically coded with CPT codes.
}

::Q-DAT-068:: What is the primary financial benefit to patients of using an in-network provider? {
~The provider waives all fees for insured patients #In-network providers do not waive all fees — patients still have cost-sharing responsibilities.
=The provider charges pre-negotiated rates, resulting in lower out-of-pocket costs #In-network providers have pre-negotiated rates with the insurer, which results in lower out-of-pocket costs for patients.
~The patient receives a tax credit for each in-network visit #Tax credits are not tied to using in-network providers.
~The patient's deductible is automatically waived #Deductibles are not automatically waived for in-network visits.
}

::Q-DAT-069:: Why do patients typically pay more when using an out-of-network provider? {
~Out-of-network providers charge higher taxes on their services #Provider charges are not taxes and are not related to tax rates.
=The provider does not have a contract with the insurer, so there are no pre-negotiated rates #Without a contract, the provider is not bound to pre-negotiated rates, so the patient bears higher costs.
~Out-of-network providers use more expensive medical equipment #Equipment cost is not the reason patients pay more for out-of-network care.
~The patient's insurance policy is cancelled when they go out of network #Using an out-of-network provider does not cancel the patient's insurance policy.
}

::Q-DAT-070:: What does it mean for a provider to be "in-network"? {
~The provider is located within the same state as the patient #Network status is determined by a contractual relationship with an insurer, not geographic location.
=The provider has a contract with the patient's health insurer to provide services at agreed-upon rates #An in-network provider has a contract with the patient's health insurer to provide services at pre-negotiated rates.
~The provider accepts only Medicare patients #In-network status applies to any insurer, not just Medicare.
~The provider works exclusively in a hospital setting #In-network status is about the contractual relationship, not the practice setting.
}

::Q-DAT-071:: Which of the following is typically included in an Electronic Health Record (EHR)? {
~A patient's credit score and financial history #Credit scores and financial history are not part of an EHR.
=Demographics, medications, vital signs, and lab results #EHRs include clinical data such as demographics, medications, vital signs, immunizations, lab results, and radiology reports.
~The provider's malpractice insurance details #Provider insurance details are administrative records, not EHR content.
~The hospital's annual revenue reports #Hospital revenue reports are financial documents, not part of an EHR.
}

::Q-DAT-072:: How do EHRs help improve the quality of patient care? {
~By eliminating the need for physicians entirely #EHRs support physicians — they do not replace them.
=By reducing duplication of tests, decreasing treatment delays, and improving record accuracy #EHRs reduce test duplication, decrease delays, and improve accuracy by making information available electronically to authorized providers.
~By allowing patients to diagnose their own conditions #EHRs provide information to providers; they do not enable patient self-diagnosis.
~By replacing all in-person visits with telehealth sessions #EHRs are digital records, not telehealth platforms.
}

::Q-DAT-073:: What is a key characteristic of certified EHR technology? {
~It stores data in handwritten format for authenticity #Certified EHRs store data digitally in a structured format, not handwritten.
=It stores patient data in a structured format for easy retrieval, transfer, and use #Certified EHR technology stores data in a structured format that supports retrieval, transfer, and care decisions.
~It restricts data access to a single provider at a time #EHRs are designed to support access by multiple authorized providers.
~It requires data to be printed on paper before it can be shared #Certified EHRs enable electronic sharing without printing.
}

::Q-DAT-074:: What type of standards does the HIPAA Privacy Rule establish? {
~Local hospital guidelines for visitor policies #The Privacy Rule sets national standards, not local hospital guidelines.
=National standards for protecting individually identifiable health information #The Privacy Rule establishes national standards for the protection of individually identifiable health information.
~International guidelines for pharmaceutical manufacturing #HIPAA is a U.S. law, not an international pharmaceutical standard.
~State-level regulations for medical school accreditation #Medical school accreditation is handled by separate organizations, not the HIPAA Privacy Rule.
}

::Q-DAT-075:: Which of the following is an example of a physical safeguard under the HIPAA Security Rule? {
~Assigning unique login credentials to each employee #Unique login credentials are a technical safeguard.
~Conducting annual risk assessments #Risk assessments are an administrative safeguard.
=Controlling physical access to facilities where ePHI is stored #Physical safeguards protect the physical facilities, workstations, and devices where ePHI is stored or accessed.
~Encrypting emails that contain patient data #Email encryption is a technical safeguard.
}

::Q-DAT-076:: The HIPAA Breach Notification Rule requires covered entities to notify affected individuals within what timeframe? {
~Immediately upon suspecting a breach #The rule specifies "without unreasonable delay" but allows up to 60 days, not immediate notification.
~Within 24 hours of discovering a breach #24 hours is not the standard under the Breach Notification Rule.
=Without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 days after discovery #The rule requires notification without unreasonable delay and no later than 60 days after discovering the breach.
~Within one calendar year of the breach #One calendar year far exceeds the maximum allowed notification period.
}

::Q-DAT-077:: How does an EHR differ from a traditional paper chart? {
=An EHR is a digital version of a patient's medical history maintained over time #An EHR is a digital version of a patient's medical history maintained by the provider over time, unlike a paper chart.
~An EHR contains less information than a paper chart #EHRs typically contain more comprehensive and accessible data than paper charts.
~An EHR can only be accessed by the patient, not the provider #EHRs are maintained by and accessible to authorized providers.
~An EHR must be printed and filed in a cabinet to be valid #EHRs are valid in their electronic form and do not require printing.
}

::Q-DAT-078:: Which of the following best describes the purpose of ICD codes in the healthcare system? {
~To calculate provider salaries based on patient volume #Provider salaries are not determined by ICD codes.
=To provide a standardized way to classify diagnoses and inpatient procedures #ICD codes provide a standardized system for classifying medical diagnoses and inpatient procedures on claims and records.
~To determine which patients qualify for health insurance #Insurance eligibility is determined by plan rules, not ICD codes.
~To rank hospitals by quality of care #Hospital rankings are not based on ICD codes.
}

::Q-DAT-079:: Which scenario correctly applies the minimum necessary standard? {
=A billing clerk accesses only the diagnosis codes and procedure codes needed to process a claim #Accessing only the specific data elements needed for the task (billing) is a proper application of the minimum necessary standard.
~A receptionist reads a patient's full psychiatric notes to schedule an appointment #A receptionist does not need psychiatric notes to schedule an appointment — this exceeds the minimum necessary.
~An IT technician reviews all patient records to test a new software feature #Accessing all patient records for software testing is not limited to the minimum necessary.
~A hospital administrator shares complete patient files with a marketing agency #Sharing complete patient files with a marketing agency violates the minimum necessary standard.
}

::Q-DAT-080:: Which of the following is a way that EHRs help reduce delays in patient treatment? {
~By requiring patients to carry paper copies of their records to every appointment #EHRs eliminate the need for patients to carry paper records, not reinforce it.
=By making health information available electronically to authorized providers #EHRs reduce treatment delays by making health information available electronically to authorized providers when and where it is needed.
~By limiting the number of providers who can treat a patient #EHRs improve information access; they do not restrict which providers can treat a patient.
~By replacing all diagnostic testing with automated algorithms #EHRs support care decisions but do not replace diagnostic testing.
}


$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Patient

::Q-PAT-001:: A dependent is a family member covered under the subscriber's health insurance plan. {TRUE #### A dependent is indeed a family member — such as a spouse, child, or domestic partner — covered under the subscriber's plan rather than holding their own policy.}

::Q-PAT-002:: Under the Affordable Care Act, children can remain on a parent's health plan until they reach age 30. {FALSE #### Under the ACA, children can remain on a parent's plan until age 26, not age 30, regardless of marital status.}

::Q-PAT-003:: A covered entity must respond to a patient's request to access their health records within 30 days. {TRUE #### Under the HIPAA Privacy Rule, a covered entity must respond to a patient's access request within 30 days of receiving it.}

::Q-PAT-004:: Informed consent can never be waived, even in a life-threatening emergency. {FALSE #### Informed consent may be waived in life-threatening emergencies when there is not enough time to obtain consent and no authorized decision-maker is available.}

::Q-PAT-005:: An Explanation of Benefits (EOB) is a bill that the patient must pay immediately. {FALSE #### An EOB is not a bill. It is a summary from the health plan showing what was billed, what the plan paid, and what the patient owes.}

::Q-PAT-006:: Who is the subscriber on a health insurance plan? {
~A family member covered under someone else's plan #A family member covered under someone else's plan is a dependent, not the subscriber.
=The primary individual who enrolls in and holds the insurance contract #The subscriber (also called the policyholder) is the primary individual who enrolls in and holds the health insurance contract with the insurance carrier.
~The insurance company that issues the policy #The insurance company is the carrier or insurer, not the subscriber.
~The employer who sponsors the group plan #The employer sponsors the plan but is not the subscriber on an individual's policy.
}

::Q-PAT-007:: What is the annual period during which anyone can enroll in or change a Health Insurance Marketplace plan? {
~Special Enrollment Period #A Special Enrollment Period is triggered by a qualifying life event and occurs outside of Open Enrollment.
~Qualifying Life Event window #A qualifying life event triggers a Special Enrollment Period; it is not a named enrollment window.
=Open Enrollment #Open Enrollment is the annual period when anyone can enroll in, renew, or change a Marketplace plan.
~Grace Period #A grace period is time allowed to make a late payment, not an enrollment window.
}

::Q-PAT-008:: Which of the following is a qualifying life event that triggers a Special Enrollment Period? {
~Receiving a raise at work #A raise in pay is not a qualifying life event under Marketplace rules.
~Turning 30 years old #Turning 30 is not a qualifying life event for health insurance enrollment.
=Getting married #Getting married is a qualifying life event that allows a person to enroll in or change a Marketplace plan during a Special Enrollment Period.
~Changing your primary care doctor #Changing your doctor does not trigger a Special Enrollment Period.
}

::Q-PAT-009:: Under HIPAA, which right allows patients to request corrections to their health records? {
~Right to access #The right to access allows patients to view and obtain copies of their records, not to correct them.
=Right to amendment #Patients have the right to request amendments (corrections) to their health records if they believe the information is inaccurate or incomplete.
~Right to complaint #The right to complaint lets patients file a grievance with HHS, not correct records.
~Right to portability #Portability relates to transferring coverage between plans, not correcting health records.
}

::Q-PAT-010:: If a patient believes their HIPAA privacy rights have been violated, where can they file a complaint? {
~The state governor's office #The state governor's office does not handle HIPAA complaints.
~The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) #The FTC handles consumer protection matters but is not the designated body for HIPAA complaints.
=The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) #Patients have the right to file a complaint with the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) if they believe their HIPAA privacy rights have been violated.
~The local police department #Local police do not handle HIPAA privacy complaints.
}

::Q-PAT-011:: What is informed consent? {
~A form that assigns payment to the provider #Assignment of payment is a billing arrangement, not informed consent.
~A billing agreement between the patient and the insurance company #A billing agreement relates to financial terms, not the clinical decision-making process.
=A process in which a clinician explains the risks, benefits, and alternatives of a proposed treatment so the patient can make a voluntary decision #Informed consent is a communication process in which a clinician explains the risks, benefits, and alternatives of a proposed procedure or treatment so the patient can make a voluntary, informed decision.
~A notice that describes how the provider will use patient health information #That describes a Notice of Privacy Practices, which is a separate HIPAA requirement.
}

::Q-PAT-012:: What is the term for the amount a patient pays each month to maintain health insurance coverage? {
~Deductible #A deductible is the amount paid out of pocket before the plan starts paying, not the monthly payment to maintain coverage.
~Copayment #A copayment is a fixed dollar amount paid at the time of a visit, not the monthly coverage payment.
=Premium #A premium is the amount a patient pays — usually monthly — to maintain health insurance coverage, regardless of whether they use medical services.
~Coinsurance #Coinsurance is a percentage of costs shared after the deductible is met, not the monthly payment.
}

::Q-PAT-013:: A patient pays 20% of a covered service's cost after meeting the deductible, while the plan pays 80%. What is the patient's 20% share called? {
~Copayment #A copayment is a fixed dollar amount (e.g., $25), not a percentage of the cost.
~Deductible #The deductible is the total amount a patient must pay before insurance begins sharing costs, not a percentage split.
~Premium #The premium is the monthly payment to maintain coverage, not a cost-sharing percentage.
=Coinsurance #Coinsurance is the percentage of a covered service's cost that the patient pays after meeting the deductible.
}

::Q-PAT-014:: What happens when a patient reaches their out-of-pocket maximum for the plan year? {
~The patient's coverage is terminated #Reaching the out-of-pocket maximum does not terminate coverage; it provides financial protection.
~The patient must pay a higher coinsurance rate #The coinsurance rate does not increase at the out-of-pocket maximum; instead, the plan covers 100%.
=The health plan pays 100% of covered costs for the remainder of the year #Once a patient reaches the out-of-pocket maximum, the health plan pays 100% of covered costs for the remainder of the plan year.
~The deductible resets to zero #The deductible does not reset when the out-of-pocket maximum is reached.
}

::Q-PAT-015:: Why is patient engagement important in healthcare? {
~It allows patients to bill their own insurance claims #Patient engagement does not involve patients billing their own claims.
~It reduces the need for health insurance coverage #Engagement does not reduce the need for insurance; it helps patients navigate the system more effectively.
=Higher patient engagement is associated with better health outcomes and lower costs #Research shows that higher patient activation and engagement is associated with better health outcomes and lower costs.
~It transfers clinical decision-making from providers to patients #Patient engagement supports shared decision-making; it does not transfer full clinical authority to patients.
}

::Q-PAT-016:: The subscriber is also known as the policyholder on a health insurance plan. {TRUE #### The subscriber and the policyholder are the same person — the primary individual who enrolls in and holds the health insurance contract.}

::Q-PAT-017:: A dependent must be employed by the same company as the subscriber to receive coverage. {FALSE #### A dependent is a family member — such as a spouse, child, or domestic partner — covered under the subscriber's plan. Employment at the same company is not required.}

::Q-PAT-018:: Under the ACA, a child's marital status does not affect their ability to stay on a parent's health plan until age 26. {TRUE #### The ACA requires health plans to allow children to remain on a parent's plan until age 26 regardless of marital status.}

::Q-PAT-019:: Outside of Open Enrollment, a person can enroll in a Marketplace plan at any time for any reason. {FALSE #### Outside of Open Enrollment, a person can only enroll in or change a Marketplace plan if they experience a qualifying life event that triggers a Special Enrollment Period.}

::Q-PAT-020:: Most Special Enrollment Periods give a person 60 days to select a new health plan after a qualifying life event. {TRUE #### Most SEPs provide a 60-day window before or after the qualifying life event to enroll in or change a health plan.}

::Q-PAT-021:: A provider may charge a patient a fee for searching for and retrieving their health records. {FALSE #### A provider may charge a reasonable fee for copying and mailing health records, but cannot charge for searching for or retrieving them.}

::Q-PAT-022:: A patient can direct a covered entity to send their health information to a third party, such as another doctor. {TRUE #### Under HIPAA, patients have the right to direct a covered entity to send a copy of their health information to a designated third party.}

::Q-PAT-023:: The Notice of Privacy Practices is a bill sent to the patient after each doctor visit. {FALSE #### The Notice of Privacy Practices is a plain-language document explaining how a covered entity may use and disclose the patient's health information. It is not a bill.}

::Q-PAT-024:: For children who cannot consent on their own, a parent or legal guardian provides informed consent for medical treatment. {TRUE #### Competent adults consent for themselves, while a parent or legal guardian provides informed consent on behalf of a child.}

::Q-PAT-025:: A deductible is a fixed dollar amount paid at the time of each doctor visit. {FALSE #### A fixed dollar amount paid at the time of a visit is a copayment. A deductible is the total amount a patient must pay out of pocket each year before the plan begins to pay its share.}

::Q-PAT-026:: Premiums must be paid regardless of whether the patient uses any medical services during that period. {TRUE #### A premium is paid — usually monthly — to maintain health insurance coverage, whether or not the patient sees a doctor or uses any services.}

::Q-PAT-027:: After reaching the out-of-pocket maximum, the patient continues to pay coinsurance for covered services. {FALSE #### Once the out-of-pocket maximum is reached, the health plan pays 100% of covered costs for the remainder of the plan year. The patient no longer pays coinsurance, copays, or deductible amounts.}

::Q-PAT-028:: Patients should compare their Explanation of Benefits with the provider's bill before making a payment. {TRUE #### Patients should compare the EOB from their health plan with the bill from the provider to confirm that services and amounts match before paying.}

::Q-PAT-029:: Higher patient activation is associated with better health outcomes and lower costs. {TRUE #### Research shows that patients who are more knowledgeable, skilled, and confident in managing their care tend to have better outcomes and incur lower healthcare costs.}

::Q-PAT-030:: Eligibility for employer-sponsored health insurance and Marketplace coverage is determined by the same set of rules. {FALSE #### Employer-sponsored coverage eligibility is determined by the employer's plan rules, while Marketplace eligibility depends on factors such as income, household size, and residency.}

::Q-PAT-031:: Under HIPAA, patients have a legal, enforceable right to access their protected health information held by covered entities. {TRUE #### The HIPAA Privacy Rule gives patients a legal and enforceable right to access and obtain copies of their PHI from covered entities such as doctors, hospitals, and health plans.}

::Q-PAT-032:: Any adult, regardless of mental competency, can give valid informed consent for medical treatment. {FALSE #### Only competent adults — those who can understand the information and make a voluntary decision — can give valid informed consent. Adults who lack competency rely on an authorized decision-maker.}

::Q-PAT-033:: A copayment amount varies based on the total cost of the medical service. {FALSE #### A copayment is a fixed dollar amount — for example $25 — that does not change based on the total cost of the service. The amount that varies with service cost is coinsurance.}

::Q-PAT-034:: Having a baby is a qualifying life event that can trigger a Special Enrollment Period. {TRUE #### Having a baby is one of the qualifying life events — along with getting married, losing coverage, or moving — that triggers a Special Enrollment Period.}

::Q-PAT-035:: Which term best describes a spouse or child covered under someone else's health insurance plan? {
~Subscriber #The subscriber is the person who holds the insurance contract, not the person covered under it.
~Policyholder #Policyholder is another term for the subscriber, not for family members on the plan.
=Dependent #A dependent is a family member — such as a spouse, child, or domestic partner — who is covered under the subscriber's plan.
~Beneficiary #Beneficiary is a general insurance term; in health insurance, the correct term is dependent.
}

::Q-PAT-036:: Until what age can children remain on a parent's health plan under the Affordable Care Act? {
~21 #Age 21 was a common cutoff before the ACA, but the law extended it to 26.
~24 #Age 24 is not the correct threshold under the ACA.
=26 #The ACA requires health plans that offer dependent coverage to allow children to stay on a parent's plan until age 26.
~30 #Age 30 exceeds the ACA requirement, which sets the limit at 26.
}

::Q-PAT-037:: Which of the following is NOT a qualifying life event for a Special Enrollment Period? {
~Losing existing health coverage #Losing health coverage is a qualifying life event that triggers a Special Enrollment Period.
~Moving to a new state #Moving to a new coverage area is a qualifying life event.
=Receiving a promotion at work #A promotion does not change coverage status and is not a qualifying life event. Losing coverage, moving, and having a baby are all qualifying life events.
~Having a baby #Having a baby is a qualifying life event.
}

::Q-PAT-038:: How many days do most Special Enrollment Periods give a person to select a new health plan? {
~30 days #30 days is the HIPAA response deadline for records requests, not the SEP window.
~45 days #45 days is not the standard SEP window.
=60 days #Most Special Enrollment Periods provide a 60-day window before or after the qualifying life event to select a new health plan.
~90 days #90 days exceeds the standard 60-day SEP window.
}

::Q-PAT-039:: Marketplace plan eligibility depends on which of the following factors? {
~The applicant's job title and years of experience #Job title and experience are not factors in Marketplace eligibility.
=Income, household size, and residency #Marketplace eligibility is determined by factors such as income, household size, and state residency.
~The applicant's credit score #Credit score has no bearing on health insurance Marketplace eligibility.
~The applicant's medical history #Under the ACA, medical history cannot be used to determine eligibility for Marketplace plans.
}

::Q-PAT-040:: Which of the following is a covered entity required to provide patients access to under HIPAA? {
~The provider's financial statements #Provider financial statements are not part of the patient's PHI.
~Other patients' health records #Sharing other patients' records would violate HIPAA privacy protections.
=The patient's own protected health information #Under HIPAA, covered entities must provide patients with access to their own protected health information.
~The provider's internal staffing schedules #Staffing schedules are internal business records, not patient health information.
}

::Q-PAT-041:: Within how many days must a covered entity respond to a patient's request to access their health records? {
~7 days #7 days is too short; HIPAA allows up to 30 days.
~14 days #14 days is not the HIPAA-required timeframe.
=30 days #HIPAA requires a covered entity to respond to a patient's access request within 30 days of receiving it.
~60 days #60 days is the SEP enrollment window, not the records access deadline.
}

::Q-PAT-042:: When a patient believes information in their health record is inaccurate, what HIPAA right can they exercise? {
~Right to delete all records #HIPAA does not give patients a blanket right to delete all records.
=Right to amendment #Patients have the right to request amendments — corrections — to their health records if they believe the information is inaccurate or incomplete.
~Right to transfer their provider license #Provider licensing is unrelated to patient record rights.
~Right to waive all future treatment #Waiving future treatment is not a HIPAA records right.
}

::Q-PAT-043:: A provider may charge a reasonable fee for which of the following when a patient requests their records? {
~Searching for the records #HIPAA prohibits charging for searching for records.
~Retrieving the records from storage #Retrieval costs cannot be passed to the patient under HIPAA.
=Copying and mailing the records #Providers may charge a reasonable fee for copying and mailing health records but cannot charge for the search-and-retrieval effort.
~Locating the records in the system #Locating records is part of the search process, which cannot be charged.
}

::Q-PAT-044:: A patient wants their medical records sent to a new specialist. Under HIPAA, what can the patient do? {
~Nothing — only the original provider can decide where records go #Patients have the right to direct where their records are sent.
=Direct the covered entity to send a copy to the specialist #Patients can direct a covered entity to send a copy of their health information to a third party of their choice, such as another doctor.
~File a lawsuit to obtain the records #A lawsuit is not required; HIPAA provides this right directly.
~Ask the insurance company to transfer the records automatically #The request goes to the covered entity holding the records, not the insurance company.
}

::Q-PAT-045:: Where can a patient file a complaint if they believe their HIPAA privacy rights have been violated? {
~The local courthouse #HIPAA complaints are handled by HHS, not the local court system.
~The Federal Reserve Board #The Federal Reserve Board oversees banking, not health privacy.
=The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) #Patients may file a complaint with HHS if they believe a covered entity has violated their HIPAA privacy rights.
~The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) #The IRS handles tax matters, not HIPAA enforcement.
}

::Q-PAT-046:: What does the Notice of Privacy Practices explain to a patient? {
~The total cost of upcoming medical procedures #Procedure costs are discussed separately and are not part of the Notice of Privacy Practices.
=How the covered entity may use and disclose the patient's health information #The Notice of Privacy Practices is a plain-language document explaining how the entity may use and disclose the patient's health information.
~The patient's remaining deductible balance #Deductible balances appear on insurance statements, not in the Notice of Privacy Practices.
~The provider's malpractice insurance coverage #Malpractice coverage is unrelated to privacy practices.
}

::Q-PAT-047:: Who is required to give patients a Notice of Privacy Practices? {
~Only hospitals #The requirement applies to all covered health care providers, not just hospitals.
~Only pharmacies #Pharmacies are included, but they are not the only covered entities required to provide the notice.
=Health care providers and health plans #The HIPAA Privacy Rule requires health care providers and health plans to give patients a Notice of Privacy Practices.
~Only government agencies #The requirement applies to covered entities in both the public and private sectors.
}

::Q-PAT-048:: Which of the following must a clinician explain during the informed consent process? {
~The patient's insurance deductible amount #Insurance details are not part of the informed consent discussion.
=The risks, benefits, and alternatives of the proposed treatment #Informed consent requires the clinician to explain the risks, benefits, and alternatives of a proposed procedure or treatment.
~The provider's personal medical history #The provider's personal health is irrelevant to informed consent.
~The hospital's visiting hours #Visiting hours are an administrative matter, not part of informed consent.
}

::Q-PAT-049:: In which situation may informed consent be waived? {
~When the patient is in a hurry to leave the hospital #A patient's schedule does not justify waiving informed consent.
~When the procedure is minor and low-risk #Even minor procedures generally require some form of consent.
=When there is a life-threatening emergency and no authorized decision-maker is available #Informed consent may be waived in life-threatening emergencies when there is not enough time to obtain consent and no authorized decision-maker is available.
~When the provider has performed the procedure many times before #The provider's experience level does not waive the consent requirement.
}

::Q-PAT-050:: Who provides informed consent for a minor's medical treatment? {
~The minor themselves #Minors generally cannot provide their own informed consent.
=A parent or legal guardian #For children, a parent or legal guardian provides informed consent on their behalf.
~The insurance company #Insurance companies do not provide medical consent for patients.
~The hospital administrator #Hospital administrators do not consent on behalf of patients.
}

::Q-PAT-051:: What is a deductible in health insurance? {
~The monthly payment to keep the insurance policy active #The monthly payment is the premium, not the deductible.
~A fixed dollar amount paid at each doctor visit #A fixed amount per visit is a copayment.
=The amount a patient must pay out of pocket each year before the plan begins to pay its share #A deductible is the annual amount a patient must pay out of pocket for covered services before the insurance plan begins to pay.
~The percentage of costs the patient pays after meeting a threshold #A percentage share of costs is coinsurance.
}

::Q-PAT-052:: A patient pays a flat $30 each time they visit a doctor. What is this payment called? {
~Premium #A premium is the monthly cost of maintaining coverage, not a per-visit charge.
~Deductible #A deductible is an annual out-of-pocket threshold, not a per-visit flat fee.
=Copayment #A copayment (copay) is a fixed dollar amount a patient pays for a covered service at the time of the visit.
~Coinsurance #Coinsurance is a percentage of costs, not a flat dollar amount.
}

::Q-PAT-053:: After meeting the deductible, a patient pays 30% and the plan pays 70% of covered service costs. What is the patient's 30% share called? {
~Copayment #A copayment is a fixed dollar amount, not a percentage.
~Premium #A premium is the monthly payment for coverage, not a cost-sharing percentage.
=Coinsurance #Coinsurance is the percentage of a covered service's cost that the patient pays after meeting the deductible.
~Out-of-pocket maximum #The out-of-pocket maximum is the annual cap on patient spending, not a percentage share.
}

::Q-PAT-054:: What is the out-of-pocket maximum? {
~The most a provider can charge for a single service #Provider charges are separate from the patient's out-of-pocket maximum.
=The most a patient will pay for covered services in a plan year before the plan pays 100% #The out-of-pocket maximum is the most a patient will pay for covered services in a plan year; once reached, the health plan pays 100% of covered costs.
~The total amount the insurance company pays over a patient's lifetime #Lifetime maximums are a different concept and were largely eliminated by the ACA.
~The maximum premium a plan can charge per month #Premium limits are unrelated to the out-of-pocket maximum.
}

::Q-PAT-055:: What does an Explanation of Benefits (EOB) show? {
~The patient's credit score and payment history #Credit scores are not included in an EOB.
=What was billed, what the plan paid, and what the patient owes #An EOB is a summary from the health plan showing what was billed, what the plan paid, and what the patient may owe.
~The provider's internal cost of delivering care #Internal provider costs are not disclosed on an EOB.
~The patient's complete medical history #An EOB is a financial document, not a medical record.
}

::Q-PAT-056:: Why should a patient compare their EOB with the provider's bill? {
~To verify that the provider is board-certified #Board certification is verified through medical boards, not billing documents.
=To confirm that services and amounts match before making a payment #Patients should compare the EOB with the provider bill to confirm that services and amounts match and to catch any billing errors.
~To check the insurance company's financial rating #Insurance company ratings are not shown on EOBs or provider bills.
~To see which medications are on the formulary #Formulary information is separate from billing statements.
}

::Q-PAT-057:: What does patient engagement refer to? {
~The number of times a patient visits the emergency room #ER visit frequency is a utilization metric, not a measure of engagement.
=A patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence to actively participate in their own health care #Patient engagement refers to a patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence to actively participate in their own health care decisions.
~The provider's effort to market services to patients #Marketing efforts are provider activities, not a patient characteristic.
~The length of time a patient has been enrolled in a plan #Enrollment duration is unrelated to a patient's active participation in their care.
}

::Q-PAT-058:: Which of the following best describes the relationship between a subscriber and a dependent? {
~The subscriber works for the dependent's employer #The subscriber's employment relationship is with their own employer, not the dependent's.
=The subscriber holds the insurance contract and the dependent is a covered family member #The subscriber is the primary individual who holds the insurance contract, and the dependent is a family member covered under that contract.
~The dependent selects the insurance plan and the subscriber pays for it #The subscriber, not the dependent, selects and holds the plan.
~The subscriber and dependent must live at the same address #Living at the same address is not a universal requirement for dependent status.
}

::Q-PAT-059:: Which of the following people can be a dependent on a subscriber's health plan? {
~The subscriber's coworker #Coworkers are not family members and cannot be dependents on a personal plan.
~The subscriber's neighbor #Neighbors do not qualify as dependents.
=The subscriber's spouse #A dependent is a family member — such as a spouse, child, or domestic partner — who is covered under the subscriber's plan.
~The subscriber's insurance agent #An insurance agent is a business contact, not a dependent.
}

::Q-PAT-060:: What is Open Enrollment? {
~A penalty-free period after missing a premium payment #A grace period for missed premiums is different from Open Enrollment.
=The annual period when anyone can enroll in, renew, or change a Marketplace plan #Open Enrollment is the annual period when anyone can enroll in, renew, or change a Health Insurance Marketplace plan.
~A one-time enrollment opportunity available only to new employees #New employee enrollment is part of employer-sponsored plans, not the Marketplace Open Enrollment period.
~A government program that automatically enrolls uninsured citizens #The Marketplace does not automatically enroll individuals.
}

::Q-PAT-061:: A person loses their employer-sponsored health insurance. What enrollment opportunity becomes available? {
~Open Enrollment begins immediately #Losing coverage does not restart Open Enrollment; it triggers a Special Enrollment Period.
=A Special Enrollment Period triggered by the qualifying life event #Losing existing health coverage is a qualifying life event that triggers a Special Enrollment Period, allowing the person to enroll in a Marketplace plan outside of Open Enrollment.
~Automatic enrollment in Medicaid #Medicaid enrollment depends on income eligibility, not automatic assignment.
~A one-year waiting period before any new enrollment #There is no mandatory one-year waiting period; a 60-day SEP window applies.
}

::Q-PAT-062:: Which factor determines eligibility for employer-sponsored health insurance? {
~The employee's household income #Household income is relevant to Marketplace eligibility, not employer-sponsored plans.
=The employer's plan rules #Eligibility for employer-sponsored health insurance is determined by the employer's plan rules, such as work hours and employment status.
~The employee's state of residency #State residency affects Marketplace eligibility, not typically employer plan eligibility.
~The employee's credit history #Credit history does not determine health insurance eligibility.
}

::Q-PAT-063:: Which of the following can a patient request under HIPAA besides accessing their own records? {
~Deleting all records from every provider they have ever visited #HIPAA does not grant a blanket right to delete all records across all providers.
=Amendments to inaccurate or incomplete information in their records #Under HIPAA, patients have the right to request amendments to their health records if they believe the information is inaccurate or incomplete.
~A copy of another patient's records for comparison #Accessing another patient's records would violate HIPAA privacy rules.
~A refund of all copayments made in the past year #Copayment refunds are a billing matter, not a HIPAA privacy right.
}

::Q-PAT-064:: A patient asks their doctor's office to send medical records to a family member. Under HIPAA, which statement is correct? {
~The office must refuse because records can only go to the patient #HIPAA allows patients to designate third-party recipients for their records.
~The office can send the records only if the family member is a doctor #The third party does not need to be a medical professional.
=The patient can direct the covered entity to send records to a third party of their choice #Under HIPAA, patients can direct a covered entity to send a copy of their health information to a third party of their choice, including a family member.
~The office must get permission from the insurance company first #Insurance company permission is not required for patient-directed record sharing.
}

::Q-PAT-065:: Which entity enforces HIPAA and receives patient privacy complaints? {
~The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) #The CDC focuses on disease prevention and public health, not HIPAA enforcement.
~The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) #The FDA regulates food and drugs, not health information privacy.
=The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) #Patients have the right to file a HIPAA privacy complaint with HHS, which enforces the HIPAA Privacy Rule through its Office for Civil Rights.
~The Social Security Administration (SSA) #The SSA administers Social Security benefits, not HIPAA.
}

::Q-PAT-066:: When must a patient receive a Notice of Privacy Practices? {
~Only when they are admitted to a hospital #The notice is not limited to hospital admissions; all covered providers must issue it.
~Only when they file an insurance claim #Filing a claim does not trigger the notice requirement; the first encounter does.
=At or before their first encounter with a covered health care provider or health plan #HIPAA requires covered entities to provide the Notice of Privacy Practices at or before the first delivery of service, ensuring patients know how their information may be used.
~Only when they request it in writing #The covered entity must proactively provide it, not wait for a written request.
}

::Q-PAT-067:: What type of document is the Notice of Privacy Practices written in? {
~Medical terminology only clinicians can understand #The notice is specifically written to be understandable by patients, not just clinicians.
~Legal language designed for attorneys #While it has legal significance, it is written in plain language for patient comprehension.
=Plain language so patients can understand it #The Notice of Privacy Practices is a plain-language document designed so patients can understand how their health information may be used and disclosed.
~Encrypted text for security purposes #The notice is a readable document, not an encrypted file.
}

::Q-PAT-068:: Informed consent is best described as which of the following? {
~A one-time signature on an admission form #Informed consent is an ongoing dialogue, not just a single signature.
=A communication process between clinician and patient about a proposed treatment #Informed consent is a communication process in which a clinician explains the risks, benefits, and alternatives of a proposed treatment so the patient can make a voluntary, informed decision.
~A billing authorization from the insurance company #Insurance billing authorization is separate from clinical informed consent.
~A legal contract between the hospital and the patient's employer #It is a clinician-patient process, not an employer contract.
}

::Q-PAT-069:: Which of the following is NOT part of the informed consent discussion? {
~Risks of the proposed treatment #Risks are a core element of informed consent.
~Benefits of the proposed treatment #Benefits are a core element of informed consent.
=The provider's salary information #Informed consent covers risks, benefits, and alternatives of a proposed treatment. The provider's salary is irrelevant to the consent process.
~Alternatives to the proposed treatment #Alternatives are a core element of informed consent.
}

::Q-PAT-070:: An unconscious patient arrives at the emergency room with a life-threatening injury and no family is present. What happens with informed consent? {
~Treatment is delayed until a family member arrives #Delaying life-saving treatment to wait for family could result in harm or death.
~The hospital must get a court order before treating #A court order is not required in emergency situations.
=Informed consent may be waived so emergency treatment can proceed #In life-threatening emergencies where the patient cannot consent and no authorized decision-maker is available, informed consent may be waived.
~The insurance company provides consent on the patient's behalf #Insurance companies do not provide medical consent.
}

::Q-PAT-071:: Which cost-sharing component does a patient pay before the insurance plan begins covering services? {
~Copayment #Copayments are fixed per-visit fees, not the initial annual threshold.
~Premium #Premiums maintain coverage but do not count toward the deductible.
=Deductible #The deductible is the amount a patient must pay out of pocket for covered services each year before the insurance plan begins paying its share.
~Coinsurance #Coinsurance applies after the deductible has been met.
}

::Q-PAT-072:: How does a copayment differ from coinsurance? {
~A copayment is a percentage and coinsurance is a fixed amount #This reverses the definitions. Copayment is the fixed amount and coinsurance is the percentage.
=A copayment is a fixed dollar amount and coinsurance is a percentage of the cost #A copayment is a fixed dollar amount (e.g., $25), while coinsurance is a percentage of the service cost (e.g., 20%) paid after the deductible.
~A copayment applies before the deductible and coinsurance applies after #While coinsurance typically applies after the deductible, the core difference is fixed amount versus percentage.
~There is no difference; they are the same thing #They are distinct cost-sharing mechanisms.
}

::Q-PAT-073:: Which cost-sharing component is paid monthly to keep health insurance coverage active? {
~Deductible #A deductible is an annual out-of-pocket threshold, not a monthly payment.
~Coinsurance #Coinsurance is a percentage paid at the time of service, not a monthly fee.
~Copayment #A copayment is a per-visit charge, not a recurring monthly cost.
=Premium #A premium is the amount paid — usually monthly — to maintain health insurance coverage, regardless of whether the patient uses any medical services.
}

::Q-PAT-074:: Once a patient reaches their out-of-pocket maximum for the year, who pays for additional covered services? {
~The patient continues to pay copays only #After reaching the out-of-pocket maximum, the patient pays nothing more for covered services.
=The health plan pays 100% of covered costs #Once the out-of-pocket maximum is reached, the health plan pays 100% of covered costs for the remainder of the plan year.
~Costs are split 50/50 between the patient and the plan #There is no 50/50 split; the plan covers 100%.
~The patient must purchase supplemental insurance #Supplemental insurance is not required once the out-of-pocket maximum is met.
}

::Q-PAT-075:: A patient receives an EOB that lists a $500 charge, $350 paid by the plan, and $150 as the patient's responsibility. What should the patient do next? {
~Pay $500 immediately to the provider #The patient owes $150, not $500, and should verify with the provider bill first.
~Ignore the EOB since it is not a bill #While the EOB is not a bill, the patient should use it to verify the provider's bill.
=Compare the EOB with the provider's bill to confirm the amounts match before paying #Patients should compare the EOB from their health plan with the provider's bill to confirm that services and amounts match before making any payment.
~Contact the IRS to report the charge #The IRS does not handle medical billing disputes.
}

::Q-PAT-076:: What is patient activation? {
~The process of registering for a health insurance plan #Plan registration is an enrollment activity, not activation in the patient engagement sense.
=A patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence to manage their own health care #Patient activation refers to a patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence to actively participate in their own health care decisions.
~The moment a patient's insurance coverage becomes effective #Coverage effective dates are administrative, not a measure of patient engagement.
~A provider's decision to admit a patient to the hospital #Admission decisions are made by providers, not a reflection of patient activation.
}

::Q-PAT-077:: Research shows that higher patient engagement is associated with which outcome? {
~Longer hospital stays #Engaged patients tend to manage conditions more effectively, not stay longer in hospitals.
~Higher overall healthcare costs #Higher engagement is linked to lower costs, not higher costs.
=Better health outcomes and lower costs #Studies show that higher patient activation and engagement is associated with better health outcomes and lower healthcare costs.
~Fewer doctor visits and less preventive care #Engaged patients often use more preventive care, not less.
}

::Q-PAT-078:: Which of the following is an example of a domestic partner being a dependent? {
~A coworker who shares an office with the subscriber #Coworkers do not qualify as dependents based on sharing a workspace.
=A person in a committed relationship who is covered under the subscriber's health plan #A domestic partner in a committed relationship can be listed as a dependent under the subscriber's health plan, depending on the plan's rules.
~A roommate who splits rent with the subscriber #Roommates are not considered dependents on a health plan.
~A business partner who co-owns a company with the subscriber #A business partner is a professional relationship, not a dependent relationship.
}

::Q-PAT-079:: Moving to a new state is considered what type of event for health insurance purposes? {
~An open enrollment trigger #Moving does not restart Open Enrollment; it triggers a Special Enrollment Period.
~A premium adjustment event #Premium adjustments are not directly triggered by moving.
=A qualifying life event #Moving to a new coverage area is a qualifying life event that triggers a Special Enrollment Period, allowing the person to enroll in or change a Marketplace plan.
~A coverage termination event #Moving does not automatically terminate coverage, though it may require a plan change.
}

::Q-PAT-080:: Which of the following statements about a health insurance premium is correct? {
~The premium is only charged in months when the patient sees a doctor #Premiums are due every billing period regardless of utilization.
~The premium counts toward the patient's deductible #Premiums do not count toward the deductible or out-of-pocket maximum.
=The premium is paid regardless of whether the patient uses medical services #A premium is paid — usually monthly — to maintain coverage, whether or not the patient uses any medical services.
~The premium is refunded at the end of the year if no claims are filed #Premiums are not refunded based on claims activity.
}


$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Payor

::Q-PAY-001:: Medicare Part A primarily covers hospital stays. {TRUE #### Medicare Part A is Hospital Insurance and covers inpatient hospital stays, skilled nursing facility care, hospice care, and some home health services.}

::Q-PAY-002:: Medicaid is a purely federal program with no state involvement in funding. {FALSE #### Medicaid is jointly funded by the federal government and state governments. The federal share is determined by the Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FMAP).}

::Q-PAY-003:: Commercial health insurance is the most common form of health coverage in the United States. {TRUE #### Commercial (private) health insurance is indeed the most common form of health coverage in the United States.}

::Q-PAY-004:: Under HIPAA, health plans are classified as covered entities. {TRUE #### Under HIPAA, health plans are one of the three categories of covered entities, alongside healthcare providers and clearinghouses.}

::Q-PAY-005:: Medicare Part B does not require enrollees to pay a monthly premium. {FALSE #### Medicare Part B does require a monthly premium. For 2026, the standard Part B premium is $202.90 per month.}

::Q-PAY-006:: What is a payor in healthcare? {
~A patient who receives medical treatment #A patient receives care but is not necessarily the payor. The payor is the entity that pays the provider.
=An entity responsible for paying healthcare providers for services delivered to patients #A payor (also spelled payer) is an entity responsible for paying healthcare providers for services delivered to patients.
~A government agency that licenses doctors #A licensing agency regulates providers but does not pay for patient services.
~A hospital that provides inpatient care #A hospital is a provider, not a payor. Providers deliver care; payors pay for it.
}

::Q-PAY-007:: Which of the following is a government healthcare payor? {
~Aetna #Aetna is a commercial (private) health insurance company, not a government program.
=Medicare #Medicare is a federal health insurance program administered by CMS, making it a government payor.
~Blue Cross Blue Shield #Blue Cross Blue Shield is a commercial insurer, not a government program.
~UnitedHealthcare #UnitedHealthcare is a commercial insurer, not a government program.
}

::Q-PAY-008:: Which three broad categories do healthcare payors fall into? {
=Government programs, commercial insurance, and self-pay #Healthcare payors fall into three broad categories: government programs (such as Medicare and Medicaid), commercial (private) insurance, and self-pay.
~Medicare, Medicaid, and TRICARE #Medicare, Medicaid, and TRICARE are all government programs — they represent only one of the three categories.
~Hospitals, clinics, and pharmacies #Hospitals, clinics, and pharmacies are types of providers, not payors.
~HMO, PPO, and EPO #HMO, PPO, and EPO are types of commercial insurance plans, not the three broad payor categories.
}

::Q-PAY-009:: Which federal agency administers the Medicare program? {
~Food and Drug Administration (FDA) #The FDA regulates food and drugs, not health insurance programs.
~Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) #The CDC focuses on disease prevention and public health, not health insurance administration.
=Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) #Medicare is administered by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS), a federal agency within the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
~National Institutes of Health (NIH) #The NIH conducts and supports biomedical research, not health insurance administration.
}

::Q-PAY-010:: What does Medicare Part B cover? {
~Inpatient hospital stays and hospice care #Inpatient hospital stays and hospice care are covered by Medicare Part A, not Part B.
~Prescription drug coverage #Prescription drug coverage is provided by Medicare Part D, not Part B.
=Doctors' services, outpatient care, and preventive services #Medicare Part B (Medical Insurance) covers doctors' services, outpatient hospital care, durable medical equipment, and preventive services such as screenings and vaccinations.
~Dental and vision care only #Original Medicare (Parts A and B) generally does not cover routine dental and vision care.
}

::Q-PAY-011:: What primarily determines Medicaid eligibility? {
~Age and employment status #Age is the primary factor for Medicare, not Medicaid. Medicaid eligibility is income-based.
=Income and household size #Medicaid eligibility is based on income and household size rather than age, and people can apply at any time during the year.
~Military service history #Military service history determines eligibility for TRICARE or VA benefits, not Medicaid.
~Number of years of U.S. citizenship #Citizenship duration is not the primary eligibility factor for Medicaid; income and household size are.
}

::Q-PAY-012:: Which type of commercial health insurance plan typically requires a referral to see a specialist? {
~PPO (Preferred Provider Organization) #A PPO gives more flexibility to see any provider without a referral, though costs are lower when staying in-network.
=HMO (Health Maintenance Organization) #An HMO (Health Maintenance Organization) usually requires you to choose a primary care doctor and get referrals to see specialists.
~EPO (Exclusive Provider Organization) #An EPO is a type of plan that limits coverage to in-network providers but does not typically require referrals.
~POS (Point of Service) #A POS plan blends features of HMOs and PPOs but is not the plan type most commonly associated with specialist referrals.
}

::Q-PAY-013:: What is a self-pay patient? {
~A patient enrolled in Medicare Part A #A patient enrolled in Medicare Part A has government insurance coverage and is not self-pay.
~A patient covered by an employer-sponsored group health plan #A patient with employer-sponsored insurance has commercial coverage and is not self-pay.
=A patient who does not have health insurance or chooses not to file a claim with their insurer #A self-pay patient is someone who does not have health insurance or who chooses not to submit a claim to their insurance for a particular service.
~A patient whose payor has denied their claim #A claim denial does not automatically make a patient self-pay; the patient may appeal or the provider may resubmit.
}

::Q-PAY-014:: What is the most common way Americans obtain private health insurance? {
~Purchasing directly from an insurance company #Direct purchase is an option but is less common than employer-sponsored coverage.
=Through employer-sponsored group health plans #Employer-sponsored group health plans are the most common way Americans obtain private health insurance.
~Through the Health Insurance Marketplace #The Marketplace is an option for those without employer coverage but is not the most common source.
~Through Medicaid #Medicaid is a government program, not private insurance.
}

::Q-PAY-015:: Which type of health plan is exempt from HIPAA covered-entity requirements? {
~Medicare #Medicare is a government program and is a HIPAA-covered health plan.
=A group health plan with fewer than 50 participants administered solely by the employer #A group health plan with fewer than 50 participants that is administered solely by the employer is exempt from HIPAA covered-entity requirements.
~Any HMO plan #HMOs are health plans and are generally HIPAA-covered entities.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is a government program and is a HIPAA-covered health plan.
}

::Q-PAY-016:: Original Medicare consists of two parts: Part A (Hospital Insurance) and Part B (Medical Insurance). {TRUE #### Original Medicare is made up of Part A, which covers hospital and inpatient services, and Part B, which covers outpatient and physician services.}

::Q-PAY-017:: Most people pay no monthly premium for Medicare Part A because they or their spouse paid Medicare taxes for at least 10 years. {TRUE #### If a person or their spouse paid Medicare taxes for 40 or more quarters (10 years), they qualify for premium-free Part A.}

::Q-PAY-018:: Medicare is only available to people aged 65 and older. {FALSE #### While Medicare primarily serves people 65 and older, it is also available to certain people under 65 who have disabilities, End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD), or ALS.}

::Q-PAY-019:: People already receiving Social Security benefits are automatically enrolled in Medicare Part A and Part B when they become eligible. {TRUE #### Individuals who are already receiving Social Security benefits are automatically enrolled in both Part A and Part B when they reach Medicare eligibility.}

::Q-PAY-020:: Medicaid eligibility rules and covered services are identical in every state. {FALSE #### Medicaid is administered by individual states according to federal requirements, so eligibility rules and covered services can vary from state to state.}

::Q-PAY-021:: Medicaid covers eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities. {TRUE #### Medicaid is a joint federal and state program that provides health coverage to these eligible populations.}

::Q-PAY-022:: The Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FMAP) is the same for every state. {FALSE #### The FMAP varies by state based on per capita income. States with lower per capita incomes receive a higher federal share of Medicaid costs.}

::Q-PAY-023:: Unlike Medicare, Medicaid allows people to apply at any time during the year rather than only during open enrollment periods. {TRUE #### Medicaid does not have a limited enrollment period — eligible individuals can apply at any time during the year.}

::Q-PAY-024:: An EPO (Exclusive Provider Organization) plan typically covers out-of-network care for non-emergency situations. {FALSE #### An EPO limits coverage to in-network providers, meaning services from out-of-network providers are generally not covered except in emergencies.}

::Q-PAY-025:: Employer-sponsored group health plans typically share the cost of premiums between the employer and employees. {TRUE #### In employer-sponsored plans, the employer typically shares the cost of premiums with employees, making coverage more affordable.}

::Q-PAY-026:: An uninsured individual is someone who is not enrolled in any group health plan, individual health insurance coverage, or federal health care program. {TRUE #### This is the definition of an uninsured individual — a person without any form of health insurance coverage.}

::Q-PAY-027:: Under the No Surprises Act, providers are only required to give a good faith estimate if the patient specifically requests one. {FALSE #### Under the No Surprises Act, providers must give uninsured or self-pay patients a good faith estimate of expected charges before or upon scheduling a service, regardless of whether the patient requests one.}

::Q-PAY-028:: HIPAA-covered health plans include health insurance companies, HMOs, and government programs such as Medicare and Medicaid. {TRUE #### All of these are classified as health plans under HIPAA and must comply with the Privacy Rule and Security Rule.}

::Q-PAY-029:: A PPO plan requires members to choose a primary care physician before they can receive any covered services. {FALSE #### A PPO (Preferred Provider Organization) generally does not require members to choose a primary care physician or get referrals to see specialists. PPOs offer more flexibility in choosing providers.}

::Q-PAY-030:: When a patient has coverage from more than one payor, the payor that pays first is called the primary payer. {TRUE #### Coordination of benefits rules determine which payor pays first, and that payor is referred to as the primary payer.}

::Q-PAY-031:: Medicare Part B covers prescription drug costs. {FALSE #### Prescription drug coverage is provided by Medicare Part D, not Part B. Part B covers doctors' services, outpatient care, and preventive services.}

::Q-PAY-032:: Aetna, Blue Cross Blue Shield, and UnitedHealthcare are examples of government healthcare programs. {FALSE #### Aetna, Blue Cross Blue Shield, and UnitedHealthcare are major commercial (private) health insurance companies, not government programs.}

::Q-PAY-033:: Commercial health insurance can be obtained through an employer, purchased on the Health Insurance Marketplace, or bought directly from an insurance company. {TRUE #### These are the three main channels through which individuals can obtain commercial health insurance coverage.}

::Q-PAY-034:: Medicare Part A covers durable medical equipment such as wheelchairs and oxygen tanks. {FALSE #### Durable medical equipment is covered under Medicare Part B, not Part A. Part A covers inpatient hospital stays, skilled nursing facility care, hospice care, and some home health services.}

::Q-PAY-035:: Which of the following people would be eligible for Medicare under age 65? {
~A 30-year-old with a household income below the poverty line #Low income alone does not qualify someone for Medicare; that would be a factor for Medicaid eligibility.
=A 40-year-old who has been receiving Social Security Disability Insurance benefits for 24 months #Medicare is available to certain people under 65 who have disabilities, including those who have received Social Security Disability Insurance for 24 months.
~A 55-year-old who lost their employer-sponsored coverage #Losing employer coverage does not automatically make someone eligible for Medicare; they may qualify for COBRA or Marketplace coverage.
~A 60-year-old who is self-employed #Being self-employed at age 60 does not qualify someone for Medicare; the standard eligibility age is 65.
}

::Q-PAY-036:: What does the abbreviation CMS stand for? {
~Centers for Medical Standards #There is no federal agency called Centers for Medical Standards.
=Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services #CMS stands for the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services, the federal agency that administers Medicare and oversees Medicaid.
~Commission for Medical Supervision #Commission for Medical Supervision is not a real agency name.
~Council for Managed Services #Council for Managed Services is not a real agency name.
}

::Q-PAY-037:: CMS is a federal agency within which department? {
~Department of Labor #The Department of Labor oversees workplace regulations and labor standards, not Medicare or Medicaid.
=Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) #CMS is a federal agency within the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).
~Department of the Treasury #The Department of the Treasury manages government finances and tax collection, not health insurance programs.
~Department of Veterans Affairs #The Department of Veterans Affairs provides healthcare to veterans through the VA system, which is separate from Medicare.
}

::Q-PAY-038:: Which Medicare part is also known as Hospital Insurance? {
=Part A #Medicare Part A is known as Hospital Insurance because it covers inpatient hospital stays and related institutional care.
~Part B #Part B is known as Medical Insurance and covers outpatient services.
~Part C #Part C refers to Medicare Advantage, which bundles Part A and Part B through a private insurer.
~Part D #Part D provides prescription drug coverage.
}

::Q-PAY-039:: Which of the following services is covered under Medicare Part A? {
~Routine dental cleanings #Original Medicare generally does not cover routine dental care.
=Hospice care #Medicare Part A covers hospice care, along with inpatient hospital stays, skilled nursing facility care, and some home health services.
~Annual eye exams for glasses #Original Medicare generally does not cover routine eye exams for glasses.
~Prescription medications from a pharmacy #Prescription drugs are covered under Medicare Part D, not Part A.
}

::Q-PAY-040:: Why do most Medicare beneficiaries not pay a monthly premium for Part A? {
~Part A is always free for all U.S. residents #Part A is not automatically free for everyone — it is premium-free only for those who meet the work history requirement.
=They or their spouse paid Medicare taxes for at least 10 years #Most people qualify for premium-free Part A because they or their spouse paid Medicare taxes for 40 or more quarters (10 years) during their working life.
~Part A premiums are waived for anyone over age 65 #Age alone does not waive the Part A premium; the payroll tax contribution requirement must be met.
~The federal government covers Part A premiums from the general fund #Part A is primarily funded by payroll taxes, not general fund appropriations.
}

::Q-PAY-041:: Which of the following is covered by Medicare Part B? {
~Inpatient hospital stays #Inpatient hospital stays are covered under Part A.
~Skilled nursing facility care #Skilled nursing facility care is covered under Part A.
=Preventive services such as screenings and vaccinations #Medicare Part B covers preventive services such as screenings and vaccinations, along with doctors' services, outpatient care, and durable medical equipment.
~Hospice care #Hospice care is covered under Part A.
}

::Q-PAY-042:: What is the standard monthly premium for Medicare Part B in 2026? {
~$104.90 #$104.90 was a historical Part B premium amount from earlier years, not the 2026 rate.
~$170.10 #$170.10 was the Part B premium for a prior year, not 2026.
=$202.90 #The standard Medicare Part B premium for 2026 is $202.90 per month.
~$350.00 #$350.00 is not the standard Part B premium for 2026.
}

::Q-PAY-043:: What is the annual deductible for Medicare Part B in 2026? {
~$183 #$183 is not the correct Part B deductible for 2026.
~$233 #$233 was a prior year's deductible amount, not the 2026 figure.
=$283 #The annual deductible for Medicare Part B in 2026 is $283.
~$383 #$383 is higher than the actual 2026 Part B deductible.
}

::Q-PAY-044:: Who is automatically enrolled in Medicare Parts A and B upon eligibility? {
~Anyone who turns 65 #Not everyone turning 65 is automatically enrolled — only those already receiving Social Security benefits.
=People already receiving Social Security benefits #People already receiving Social Security benefits are automatically enrolled in Medicare Part A and Part B when they become eligible.
~All U.S. citizens regardless of age #Medicare eligibility has specific requirements; it is not automatic for all citizens.
~People enrolled in Medicaid #Medicaid enrollment does not automatically trigger Medicare enrollment.
}

::Q-PAY-045:: Which populations does Medicaid provide health coverage to? {
~Only children under 18 #Medicaid is not limited to children; it also covers adults, elderly individuals, and people with disabilities.
~Only elderly adults over 65 #Medicaid is not limited to the elderly; eligible people of all ages can receive coverage.
=Eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities #Medicaid covers a wide range of populations including eligible low-income adults, children, pregnant women, elderly adults, and people with disabilities.
~Only people with disabilities #People with disabilities are one eligible group, but Medicaid covers many other populations as well.
}

::Q-PAY-046:: What does the Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FMAP) determine? {
~The percentage of Medicare Part B premiums paid by the government #The FMAP applies to Medicaid funding, not Medicare Part B premiums.
=The federal government's share of Medicaid costs in each state #The FMAP determines the federal share of Medicaid funding for each state, which varies based on per capita income.
~The maximum number of Medicaid beneficiaries per state #The FMAP sets the funding share, not enrollment caps.
~The interest rate on medical debt #The FMAP has nothing to do with medical debt interest rates.
}

::Q-PAY-047:: How is the FMAP for a state calculated? {
~It is the same flat rate for all states #The FMAP is not a flat rate; it is specifically designed to vary based on each state's economic conditions.
=It varies by state based on per capita income #The FMAP varies by state based on per capita income, meaning states with lower incomes receive a higher federal contribution.
~It is based on the number of hospitals in the state #The number of hospitals does not factor into the FMAP calculation.
~It is set by the state governor each year #The FMAP is calculated using a federal formula, not set by state governors.
}

::Q-PAY-048:: Who administers the Medicaid program in each state? {
~CMS directly runs each state's Medicaid program #CMS provides oversight and federal requirements, but states administer their own programs.
=Individual states administer their own Medicaid programs according to federal requirements #Medicaid is administered by individual states according to federal requirements, which is why eligibility and services can vary from state to state.
~Private insurance companies administer Medicaid in every state #While states may contract with managed care organizations, the state government administers the program.
~The Social Security Administration runs Medicaid #The Social Security Administration manages Social Security benefits, not Medicaid.
}

::Q-PAY-049:: What is a key difference between Medicare and Medicaid eligibility? {
~Medicare is based on income; Medicaid is based on age #This reverses the criteria — Medicare is age-based and Medicaid is income-based.
=Medicare eligibility is primarily based on age; Medicaid eligibility is based on income and household size #Medicare eligibility is primarily age-based (65 and older), while Medicaid eligibility is based on income and household size.
~Both programs use the same eligibility criteria #Medicare and Medicaid have different eligibility criteria.
~Medicaid is only for people over 65; Medicare is for all ages #This reverses the programs — Medicare is primarily for those 65 and older, while Medicaid serves eligible low-income individuals of any age.
}

::Q-PAY-050:: How can someone obtain commercial health insurance? {
~Only through an employer #Employer-sponsored plans are one option, but not the only way to get commercial coverage.
~Only through the Health Insurance Marketplace #The Marketplace is one channel, but employer and direct-purchase options also exist.
=Through an employer, the Health Insurance Marketplace, or directly from an insurance company #Commercial health insurance can be obtained through an employer, purchased on the Health Insurance Marketplace, or bought directly from an insurance company.
~Only by purchasing directly from an insurance company #Direct purchase is one option, but employer-sponsored and Marketplace plans are also available.
}

::Q-PAY-051:: Which of the following is a major commercial health insurance company? {
~Medicare #Medicare is a federal government program, not a commercial insurance company.
~Medicaid #Medicaid is a joint federal-state government program, not a commercial insurer.
=UnitedHealthcare #UnitedHealthcare is one of the major commercial health insurance companies, along with Aetna and Blue Cross Blue Shield.
~TRICARE #TRICARE is a government health program for military personnel and their families.
}

::Q-PAY-052:: What does HMO stand for? {
~Health Management Office #Health Management Office is not what HMO stands for.
=Health Maintenance Organization #HMO stands for Health Maintenance Organization, a type of commercial health insurance plan.
~Hospital Medical Operations #Hospital Medical Operations is not what HMO stands for.
~Healthcare Member Options #Healthcare Member Options is not what HMO stands for.
}

::Q-PAY-053:: What does PPO stand for? {
~Primary Provider Organization #Primary Provider Organization is not what PPO stands for.
~Patient Payment Option #Patient Payment Option is not what PPO stands for.
=Preferred Provider Organization #PPO stands for Preferred Provider Organization, a type of commercial health insurance plan that offers more flexibility in choosing providers.
~Private Physician Office #Private Physician Office is not what PPO stands for.
}

::Q-PAY-054:: What does EPO stand for? {
~Employer Payment Organization #Employer Payment Organization is not what EPO stands for.
~Emergency Provider Option #Emergency Provider Option is not what EPO stands for.
~Extended Provider Office #Extended Provider Office is not what EPO stands for.
=Exclusive Provider Organization #EPO stands for Exclusive Provider Organization, a type of plan that limits coverage to in-network providers.
}

::Q-PAY-055:: What does POS stand for in health insurance? {
=Point of Service #POS stands for Point of Service, a type of plan that blends features of HMOs and PPOs.
~Plan of Support #Plan of Support is not what POS stands for.
~Provider of Specialty #Provider of Specialty is not what POS stands for.
~Program of Selection #Program of Selection is not what POS stands for.
}

::Q-PAY-056:: Which type of health plan blends features of both HMOs and PPOs? {
~EPO #An EPO limits coverage to in-network providers and does not blend HMO and PPO features.
~PPO #A PPO is its own distinct plan type focused on provider flexibility.
=POS #A POS (Point of Service) plan combines features of HMOs (such as requiring a primary care physician) with the flexibility of PPOs (allowing some out-of-network coverage).
~HMO #An HMO is its own distinct plan type focused on coordinated care through a primary care physician.
}

::Q-PAY-057:: In a PPO plan, what happens when a member sees an out-of-network provider? {
~The visit is never covered #PPOs do provide some coverage for out-of-network providers, unlike EPOs.
~The member pays the same amount as an in-network visit #Out-of-network visits usually cost more due to higher cost-sharing requirements.
=The member typically pays more than they would for an in-network visit #A PPO allows members to see out-of-network providers, but costs are typically higher than for in-network visits.
~The PPO becomes void and the member loses coverage #Seeing an out-of-network provider does not void PPO coverage.
}

::Q-PAY-058:: Why does employer-sponsored insurance typically cost less for employees than buying individual coverage? {
~The government subsidizes all employer plans #The government does not directly subsidize all employer-sponsored plans; the employer shares costs as a benefit.
=Employers typically share the cost of premiums with employees #Employer-sponsored group health plans are more affordable for employees because the employer typically shares the cost of premiums.
~Employer plans do not cover preventive care #Employer plans do cover preventive care; that is not the reason for lower cost.
~Employer plans have no deductibles #Employer plans can have deductibles; the cost advantage comes from employer premium contributions.
}

::Q-PAY-059:: A patient who chooses not to submit a claim to their insurance for a particular service is considered what type of patient for that service? {
~Insured #While the patient may have insurance, they are treated as self-pay for that specific service because they are not using their coverage.
~Dual-eligible #Dual-eligible refers to someone eligible for both Medicare and Medicaid, which is a different concept.
=Self-pay #A self-pay patient is someone who does not have insurance or who chooses not to submit a claim to their insurer for a particular service.
~Uninsured #The patient is not necessarily uninsured — they may have insurance but choose not to use it for that service.
}

::Q-PAY-060:: What does the No Surprises Act require providers to give uninsured or self-pay patients? {
~A free health screening #The Act requires cost transparency through estimates, not free screenings.
=A good faith estimate of expected charges #Under the No Surprises Act, providers must give uninsured or self-pay patients a good faith estimate of expected charges before or upon scheduling a service.
~Automatic enrollment in Medicaid #The Act does not automatically enroll anyone in Medicaid.
~A 50% discount on all services #The Act requires cost estimates, not mandatory discounts.
}

::Q-PAY-061:: When must a provider give an uninsured patient a good faith estimate under the No Surprises Act? {
~Only after the service has been completed #The estimate must be provided before or at the time of scheduling, not after the service.
=Before or upon scheduling the health care service #The No Surprises Act requires that providers give the good faith estimate before or upon scheduling the service.
~Within 90 days of the service #Waiting 90 days would defeat the purpose of helping patients plan for costs.
~Only if the patient files a formal complaint #The estimate is a proactive requirement; the patient does not need to file a complaint.
}

::Q-PAY-062:: What are the three categories of HIPAA-covered entities? {
~Hospitals, pharmacies, and laboratories #Hospitals, pharmacies, and labs may be covered providers, but this does not capture all three categories of covered entities.
=Health plans, health care providers, and clearinghouses #Under HIPAA, the three categories of covered entities are health plans, health care providers who transmit health information electronically, and health care clearinghouses.
~Medicare, Medicaid, and commercial insurers #These are types of health plans, which is only one of the three covered entity categories.
~Patients, providers, and payors #Patients are not classified as covered entities under HIPAA.
}

::Q-PAY-063:: Which of the following must comply with the HIPAA Privacy Rule and Security Rule? {
~Only government health programs #HIPAA applies to all covered health plans, not just government programs.
~Only commercial insurance companies #HIPAA applies to all covered health plans, not just commercial insurers.
=All HIPAA-covered health plans, including both government programs and commercial insurers #All HIPAA-covered health plans must comply with the Privacy Rule and Security Rule, regardless of whether they are government programs or commercial insurers.
~Only hospitals and doctors #Hospitals and doctors are covered providers, but health plans are also covered entities with their own compliance obligations.
}

::Q-PAY-064:: Which of the following is a HIPAA-covered health plan? {
~A fitness gym membership #Gym memberships are not health plans and are not covered by HIPAA.
=An employer-sponsored group health plan #Employer-sponsored group health plans are classified as HIPAA-covered health plans and must comply with HIPAA rules.
~A life insurance policy #Life insurance is not a health plan and is not covered by HIPAA's health plan requirements.
~An auto insurance policy #Auto insurance is not a health plan under HIPAA.
}

::Q-PAY-065:: Which type of group health plan is exempt from HIPAA covered-entity requirements? {
~Any plan offered by a large employer #Large employer plans are typically HIPAA-covered, not exempt.
=A plan with fewer than 50 participants that is administered solely by the employer #A group health plan with fewer than 50 participants that is administered solely by the employer is exempt from HIPAA covered-entity requirements.
~Any plan with fewer than 500 participants #The threshold is fewer than 50 participants with sole employer administration, not 500.
~Any plan that does not include dental coverage #Lack of dental coverage has no bearing on HIPAA covered-entity status.
}

::Q-PAY-066:: What is coordination of benefits? {
~A process that determines how much a patient owes after insurance pays #While patient cost-sharing is related, coordination of benefits specifically addresses the order in which multiple payors pay.
=Rules that determine which payor pays first when a patient has more than one insurance #Coordination of benefits rules determine which payor pays first when a patient has coverage from more than one payor.
~The process of enrolling in Medicare and Medicaid at the same time #Dual enrollment is a separate concept from coordination of benefits.
~A method for calculating insurance premiums #Premium calculation is unrelated to coordination of benefits.
}

::Q-PAY-067:: In coordination of benefits, what is the payor that pays first called? {
~The secondary payer #The secondary payer is the one that pays after the primary payer, not before.
~The copayer #Copayer is not a standard term in coordination of benefits.
=The primary payer #When a patient has more than one insurance, coordination of benefits rules determine which payor pays first, and that payor is called the primary payer.
~The supplemental payer #Supplemental payer is not the standard term for the first payer in coordination of benefits.
}

::Q-PAY-068:: Which of the following is NOT one of the three broad categories of healthcare payors? {
~Government programs #Government programs such as Medicare and Medicaid are one of the three broad payor categories.
~Commercial insurance #Commercial (private) insurance is one of the three broad payor categories.
~Self-pay #Self-pay is one of the three broad payor categories.
=Charitable organizations #The three broad categories of healthcare payors are government programs, commercial insurance, and self-pay. Charitable organizations are not one of the standard payor categories.
}

::Q-PAY-069:: A payor is best defined as which of the following? {
~A patient who pays a copayment at a doctor's office #A patient making a copayment is paying their share, but the payor is the insurance entity that pays the provider.
=An entity responsible for paying healthcare providers for services delivered to patients #A payor is an entity responsible for paying healthcare providers for services delivered to patients, including insurers and government programs.
~A government agency that regulates healthcare facilities #A regulatory agency oversees compliance, not payment for services.
~A hospital billing department #A billing department is part of a provider, not a payor.
}

::Q-PAY-070:: Medicare Part A covers skilled nursing facility care. Under which condition is this care typically covered? {
~When the patient requests long-term residential care #Medicare Part A does not cover long-term custodial care; it covers short-term skilled nursing following a hospital stay.
=Following a qualifying inpatient hospital stay #Medicare Part A covers skilled nursing facility care, which is typically provided after a qualifying inpatient hospital stay for rehabilitation and recovery.
~Whenever a patient needs any type of nursing care #Not all nursing care qualifies; the stay must typically follow a qualifying inpatient hospitalization.
~Only for patients under age 65 #Skilled nursing facility coverage under Part A is not restricted by age.
}

::Q-PAY-071:: Which of the following correctly describes an HMO plan? {
~It allows members to see any provider without restrictions #Seeing any provider without restrictions is more characteristic of a PPO, not an HMO.
=It usually requires members to choose a primary care doctor and get referrals for specialists #An HMO typically requires members to choose a primary care physician and obtain referrals to see specialists.
~It only covers emergency care #HMOs cover a full range of health services, not just emergency care.
~It does not have a provider network #HMOs are built around a defined provider network.
}

::Q-PAY-072:: Which commercial insurance plan type limits coverage to in-network providers but generally does not require referrals? {
~HMO #An HMO limits coverage to in-network providers but typically does require referrals.
~PPO #A PPO offers both in-network and out-of-network coverage and does not require referrals.
=EPO #An EPO (Exclusive Provider Organization) limits coverage to in-network providers but does not typically require referrals to see specialists.
~POS #A POS plan blends features of HMOs and PPOs and may require referrals.
}

::Q-PAY-073:: Which of the following is an example of a government healthcare payor? {
~Aetna #Aetna is a commercial (private) health insurance company.
~Blue Cross Blue Shield #Blue Cross Blue Shield is a commercial insurer.
=Medicaid #Medicaid is a joint federal and state government program that provides health coverage to eligible low-income populations.
~UnitedHealthcare #UnitedHealthcare is a commercial insurer.
}

::Q-PAY-074:: Which of the following describes Medicare Part B (Medical Insurance)? {
~It covers inpatient hospital stays only #Inpatient hospital stays are covered by Part A, not Part B.
=It covers doctors' services, outpatient care, durable medical equipment, and preventive services #Medicare Part B covers doctors' services, outpatient hospital care, durable medical equipment, and preventive services such as screenings and vaccinations.
~It covers prescription drugs only #Prescription drugs are covered by Part D, not Part B.
~It covers dental and vision care only #Original Medicare generally does not cover routine dental and vision care.
}

::Q-PAY-075:: What happens to the remaining balance after the primary payer pays its share? {
~The patient must always pay the full remaining balance #If the patient has a secondary insurance, it may pay some or all of the remaining balance before the patient is responsible.
=The secondary payer may cover some or all of the remaining balance #When a patient has more than one payor, the secondary payer may cover some or all of the remaining balance after the primary payer has paid its share.
~The remaining balance is automatically forgiven #The remaining balance is not automatically forgiven; it may be covered by a secondary payer or owed by the patient.
~The provider must absorb the entire remaining balance #Providers are generally not required to absorb the remaining balance; secondary coverage or patient responsibility applies.
}

::Q-PAY-076:: What is the Health Insurance Marketplace? {
~A government-run physical store where insurance is sold #The Marketplace is an online platform, not a physical store.
=A platform where individuals can compare and purchase health insurance plans, often with premium subsidies #The Health Insurance Marketplace is a platform where individuals can compare and purchase commercial health insurance plans, often with income-based premium subsidies.
~A database of all insured Americans #The Marketplace is for purchasing insurance, not a registry of insured individuals.
~An employer-only portal for group health plans #The Marketplace serves individuals and families, not just employers.
}

::Q-PAY-077:: Which condition, in addition to disabilities, can qualify someone under 65 for Medicare? {
~Type 2 diabetes #Type 2 diabetes alone does not qualify someone under 65 for Medicare.
=End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD) #Medicare is available to certain people under 65 with disabilities, End-Stage Renal Disease (ESRD), or ALS (amyotrophic lateral sclerosis).
~High blood pressure #High blood pressure alone does not qualify someone under 65 for Medicare.
~Asthma #Asthma alone does not qualify someone under 65 for Medicare.
}

::Q-PAY-078:: What is another term for a payor in healthcare? {
=Payer #Payor is also commonly spelled 'payer' — both terms refer to the entity responsible for paying healthcare providers.
~Purveyor #Purveyor means a supplier or provider, not an entity that pays for services.
~Patron #Patron means a customer or supporter, and is not a standard healthcare term for the paying entity.
~Payee #Payee is the entity that receives payment (the provider), not the one that makes payment.
}

::Q-PAY-079:: Which Medicare part covers home health services? {
~Part B only #While Part B can also cover certain home health services, Part A specifically includes some home health services in its coverage.
~Part D only #Part D covers prescription drugs, not home health services.
=Part A covers some home health services #Medicare Part A covers some home health services, along with inpatient hospital stays, skilled nursing facility care, and hospice care.
~No Medicare part covers home health services #Medicare does cover home health services under Part A and, in some cases, Part B.
}

::Q-PAY-080:: Which of the following best explains why Medicaid services vary from state to state? {
~Medicaid is a private insurance program with no government oversight #Medicaid is a government program, not a private insurance program.
=Each state administers its own Medicaid program according to federal requirements, allowing state-level variation #Medicaid is administered by individual states according to federal requirements, which means states have flexibility in setting eligibility rules and covered services beyond the federal minimum.
~The federal government randomly assigns different benefits to each state #Variation is due to state-level administration and policy decisions, not random assignment.
~Only states with high populations are allowed to offer additional services #All states have flexibility to offer additional services regardless of population size.
}


$CATEGORY: top/Healthcare Foundations/HLTHCR: Provider

::Q-PRV-001:: A healthcare provider can be either a person or a place that is licensed to give healthcare. {TRUE #### A health care provider is a person trained and licensed to give health care, or a place licensed to give health care.}

::Q-PRV-002:: Hospitals bill Medicare using the CMS-1500 claim form. {FALSE #### Hospitals are institutional providers and bill using the CMS-1450 (UB-04) form or its electronic equivalent, the 837I transaction. The CMS-1500 form is used by non-institutional providers like physician offices.}

::Q-PRV-003:: The National Provider Identifier (NPI) is a unique 10-digit number assigned to healthcare providers. {TRUE #### Every health care provider that bills Medicare must have a unique NPI, which is a standard 10-digit number used to identify the provider across all health transactions.}

::Q-PRV-004:: Medicare covers ambulance transportation regardless of the patient's medical condition. {FALSE #### Medicare covers ambulance transportation only when the patient's medical condition makes any other means of transportation contraindicated.}

::Q-PRV-005:: A healthcare provider becomes a HIPAA covered entity when it transmits health information electronically in connection with certain transactions. {TRUE #### Under HIPAA, a health care provider becomes a covered entity when it transmits health information electronically in connection with certain transactions such as claims billing.}

::Q-PRV-006:: Under Medicare law, what term is used for entities that furnish equipment or diagnostic services rather than sustained residential care? {
~Providers #Under Medicare law, 'providers' refers specifically to institutional care facilities such as hospitals, hospices, and nursing homes.
=Suppliers #Medicare law distinguishes between providers (institutional care facilities) and suppliers (entities that furnish diagnostic, therapeutic, or equipment services).
~Contractors #Contractors in Medicare typically refers to Medicare Administrative Contractors (MACs) that process claims, not entities that furnish equipment.
~Clearinghouses #Clearinghouses are entities that process electronic health transactions, not entities that furnish equipment or diagnostic services.
}

::Q-PRV-007:: Which enrollment form do physicians use to enroll in Medicare? {
~CMS-855A #CMS-855A is used by institutional providers such as hospitals, not individual physicians.
~CMS-855S #CMS-855S is used by DMEPOS suppliers, not physicians.
=CMS-855I #Physicians and non-physician practitioners enroll in Medicare using form CMS-855I.
~CMS-1500 #CMS-1500 is a claim form used for billing, not an enrollment form.
}

::Q-PRV-008:: Which of the following is an example of Durable Medical Equipment (DME)? {
~A prescription medication #Prescription medications are pharmaceutical products, not durable medical equipment.
=A wheelchair #Examples of DME include hospital beds, wheelchairs, ventilators, oxygen equipment, prosthetics, and orthotics.
~A blood test #A blood test is a laboratory service, which falls under ancillary services.
~An X-ray image #An X-ray image is a radiology service, which falls under ancillary services.
}

::Q-PRV-009:: Which claim form do non-institutional providers (such as physician offices) use to bill Medicare? {
~UB-04 (CMS-1450) #The UB-04 (CMS-1450) is used by institutional providers like hospitals, not physician offices.
=CMS-1500 #Non-institutional providers and suppliers bill Medicare using the CMS-1500 claim form or its electronic equivalent, the 837P transaction.
~CMS-855I #CMS-855I is a Medicare enrollment form for physicians, not a billing claim form.
~CMS-855A #CMS-855A is a Medicare enrollment form for institutional providers, not a billing claim form.
}

::Q-PRV-010:: What is the first step a provider must take before enrolling in Medicare? {
~Complete a PECOS application #The PECOS application is the second step. The provider must first obtain an NPI.
=Obtain a National Provider Identifier (NPI) #To enroll in Medicare, a provider must first obtain an NPI, then complete an application through PECOS, and finally work with their regional MAC.
~Contact their regional Medicare Administrative Contractor (MAC) #Working with the regional MAC is the third step in the enrollment process, not the first.
~Post a surety bond #Posting a surety bond is a requirement specific to DMEPOS suppliers, not the first step for all providers.
}

::Q-PRV-011:: Which of the following is an example of an ancillary service? {
~An inpatient hospital stay #An inpatient hospital stay is a service provided by an institutional provider, not classified as an ancillary service.
~Ambulance transportation #Ambulance transportation is its own provider category (transportation), not an ancillary service.
=Laboratory tests #Ancillary services include laboratory tests, radiology, pharmacy services, and other diagnostic or therapeutic services that support a patient's primary care.
~A wheelchair rental #A wheelchair rental falls under Durable Medical Equipment (DME), not ancillary services.
}

::Q-PRV-012:: How long does a Medicare enrollment application submitted through PECOS typically take to process? {
~7 days #7 days is too short. Online PECOS applications take approximately 30 days to process.
=30 days #Medicare enrollment applications submitted online through PECOS process in approximately 30 days.
~65 days #65 days is the approximate processing time for paper applications, not online PECOS submissions.
~90 days #90 days is longer than the typical processing time for either online or paper applications.
}

::Q-PRV-013:: What must a state Medicaid agency verify before approving a provider's enrollment? {
~That the provider has at least five years of experience #There is no federal Medicaid requirement for a minimum number of years of experience.
=That the provider holds an unrestricted license #State Medicaid agencies must verify that a provider holds an unrestricted license before approving enrollment.
~That the provider is enrolled in Medicare Part B #Medicare Part B enrollment is not a prerequisite for Medicaid provider enrollment.
~That the provider has completed a residency program #While residency may be required for licensure, the Medicaid enrollment requirement is specifically about holding an unrestricted license.
}

::Q-PRV-014:: Which of the following is NOT an institutional provider under Medicare? {
~Hospital #Hospitals are institutional providers under Medicare.
~Skilled nursing facility #Skilled nursing facilities are institutional providers under Medicare.
=Physician office #Institutional providers include hospitals, critical access hospitals, skilled nursing facilities, home health agencies, and hospices. A physician office is a non-institutional provider setting.
~Hospice #Hospices are institutional providers under Medicare.
}

::Q-PRV-015:: What additional requirements must DMEPOS suppliers meet to enroll in Medicare, beyond submitting form CMS-855S? {
~Complete a residency program and pass a board exam #Residency programs and board exams are requirements for physicians, not DMEPOS suppliers.
=Obtain accreditation from a CMS-approved organization and post a $50,000 surety bond #DMEPOS suppliers must obtain accreditation from a CMS-approved organization and post a $50,000 surety bond per NPI to enroll in Medicare.
~Register with the state pharmacy board and obtain a DEA number #Pharmacy board registration and DEA numbers relate to pharmacies and controlled substances, not DMEPOS enrollment.
~Submit a paper application and complete an in-person interview #There is no in-person interview requirement. The additional requirements are accreditation and a surety bond.
}

::Q-PRV-016:: A physician office is a common outpatient setting where patients receive evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment from a licensed physician. {TRUE #### A physician office is a common provider setting where patients receive outpatient evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment from a licensed physician.}

::Q-PRV-017:: Under Medicare law, the terms "provider" and "supplier" mean the same thing. {FALSE #### Medicare law distinguishes between providers (institutional care facilities such as hospitals, hospices, and nursing homes) and suppliers (entities that furnish diagnostic, therapeutic, or equipment services rather than sustained residential care).}

::Q-PRV-018:: Durable Medical Equipment must have an expected life of at least three years. {TRUE #### DME is equipment that can withstand repeated use and has an expected life of at least three years, among other criteria.}

::Q-PRV-019:: DMEPOS suppliers can enroll in Medicare using the same form that physicians use. {FALSE #### DMEPOS suppliers enroll using form CMS-855S, which is separate from the CMS-855I form used by physicians and non-physician practitioners.}

::Q-PRV-020:: Emergency air ambulance transport by airplane or helicopter can be covered by Medicare when ground ambulance cannot meet the patient's needs. {TRUE #### Emergency air ambulance transport by airplane or helicopter is covered by Medicare when immediate transport is needed and ground ambulance cannot provide it.}

::Q-PRV-021:: The Medicare ambulance fee schedule applies only to private ambulance companies. {FALSE #### The Medicare ambulance fee schedule applies to volunteer, municipal, private, and independent ambulance suppliers as well as institutional providers like hospitals.}

::Q-PRV-022:: Clinical laboratories may only operate as independent, stand-alone facilities. {FALSE #### Clinical laboratories operate in many settings including hospitals, physician offices, pharmacies, ambulatory surgery centers, and as independent labs.}

::Q-PRV-023:: Providers are required to submit Medicare claims electronically under the Administrative Simplification Compliance Act, unless they qualify for a waiver. {TRUE #### Providers are required to submit Medicare claims electronically under ASCA unless they qualify for a waiver.}

::Q-PRV-024:: Paper Medicare enrollment applications process faster than online PECOS applications. {FALSE #### Online PECOS applications process in approximately 30 days, while paper applications take approximately 65 days.}

::Q-PRV-025:: Medicaid provider enrollment is managed at the federal level by CMS, with no state involvement. {FALSE #### Each state administers its own Medicaid provider enrollment process and may impose requirements beyond the federal minimums set by CMS.}

::Q-PRV-026:: HIPAA-covered providers must comply with both the Privacy Rule and the Security Rule. {TRUE #### HIPAA-covered providers must comply with the Privacy Rule and Security Rule, which require safeguards to protect patient health information, training for employees, and contracts with business associates.}

::Q-PRV-027:: Most pharmacies are HIPAA-covered entities because they transmit health information electronically. {TRUE #### Most doctors, clinics, hospitals, psychologists, chiropractors, nursing homes, pharmacies, and dentists are HIPAA-covered entities because they transmit health information electronically.}

::Q-PRV-028:: A home health agency is classified as a supplier rather than an institutional provider under Medicare. {FALSE #### Home health agencies are institutional providers under Medicare, along with hospitals, critical access hospitals, skilled nursing facilities, and hospices.}

::Q-PRV-029:: DME is generally useful to a person even without an illness or injury. {FALSE #### One of the criteria for DME is that it is generally not useful to a person in the absence of illness or injury.}

::Q-PRV-030:: The electronic equivalent of the CMS-1500 claim form is the 837P transaction. {TRUE #### Non-institutional providers and suppliers bill using the CMS-1500 claim form or its electronic equivalent, the 837P transaction.}

::Q-PRV-031:: Nurse practitioners and physician assistants enroll in Medicare using the same form as physicians. {TRUE #### Physicians and non-physician practitioners such as nurse practitioners and physician assistants enroll in Medicare using form CMS-855I.}

::Q-PRV-032:: HIPAA-covered providers are not required to have contracts with their business associates. {FALSE #### HIPAA-covered providers must comply with the Privacy Rule and Security Rule, which require contracts with business associates among other safeguards.}

::Q-PRV-033:: DME must be appropriate for use in a patient's home. {TRUE #### One of the defining criteria for DME is that it is appropriate for use in a patient's home.}

::Q-PRV-034:: A state Medicaid agency may impose enrollment requirements that exceed the federal minimums set by CMS. {TRUE #### Each state administers its own Medicaid provider enrollment process and may impose requirements beyond the federal minimums set by CMS.}

::Q-PRV-035:: Which of the following best describes a healthcare provider? {
~An insurance company that pays claims #An insurance company is a payor, not a provider.
=A person or place licensed to give healthcare #A health care provider is a person trained and licensed to give health care, or a place licensed to give health care.
~A government agency that regulates hospitals #A government agency that regulates hospitals is a regulatory body, not a provider.
~A patient who receives medical services #A patient is the recipient of healthcare services, not the provider.
}

::Q-PRV-036:: Under Medicare, which of the following is classified as a "provider" rather than a "supplier"? {
~A DME company #A DME company furnishes equipment and is classified as a supplier under Medicare.
=A hospital #Medicare law classifies institutional care facilities such as hospitals, hospices, and nursing homes as providers. Entities furnishing equipment or diagnostic services are classified as suppliers.
~A diagnostic laboratory #A diagnostic laboratory furnishes diagnostic services and is classified as a supplier.
~A prosthetics manufacturer #A prosthetics manufacturer furnishes equipment and is classified as a supplier.
}

::Q-PRV-037:: Which type of care does a physician office primarily provide? {
~Inpatient surgical care #Inpatient surgical care is typically provided in hospitals, not physician offices.
~Long-term residential care #Long-term residential care is provided by nursing homes or similar facilities.
=Outpatient evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment #A physician office is a common provider setting where patients receive outpatient evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment from a licensed physician.
~Emergency trauma services #Emergency trauma services are provided by hospital emergency departments.
}

::Q-PRV-038:: Which form do hospitals use to enroll in Medicare? {
~CMS-855I #CMS-855I is used by individual physicians and non-physician practitioners, not hospitals.
~CMS-855S #CMS-855S is used by DMEPOS suppliers, not hospitals.
=CMS-855A #Hospitals are institutional providers that enroll in Medicare using form CMS-855A.
~CMS-1500 #CMS-1500 is a billing claim form, not an enrollment form.
}

::Q-PRV-039:: Which of the following is classified as an institutional provider under Medicare? {
~An independent clinical laboratory #Independent clinical laboratories are classified as suppliers, not institutional providers.
~A DME supplier #DME suppliers are classified as suppliers, not institutional providers.
=A home health agency #Institutional providers include hospitals, critical access hospitals, skilled nursing facilities, home health agencies, and hospices.
~A physician in private practice #A physician in private practice is a non-institutional provider.
}

::Q-PRV-040:: Which of the following is NOT one of the criteria for equipment to qualify as Durable Medical Equipment? {
~It can withstand repeated use #Withstanding repeated use is one of the standard criteria for DME.
~It has an expected life of at least three years #An expected life of at least three years is one of the standard criteria for DME.
=It must be prescribed by a specialist physician #DME must withstand repeated use, have a life of at least three years, serve a medical purpose, not be useful without illness or injury, and be appropriate for home use. There is no requirement that it be prescribed by a specialist.
~It is appropriate for use in the patient's home #Home appropriateness is one of the standard criteria for DME.
}

::Q-PRV-041:: Which of the following is an example of DME? {
~A stethoscope used by a physician #A stethoscope is a tool used by a clinician during care delivery, not equipment prescribed for the patient.
=A hospital bed for home use #Examples of DME include hospital beds, wheelchairs, ventilators, oxygen equipment, prosthetics, and orthotics.
~A bottle of prescription medication #Prescription medication is a pharmaceutical product, not durable medical equipment.
~A bandage applied in a clinic #A bandage is a disposable medical supply, not durable equipment.
}

::Q-PRV-042:: Orthotics such as back and neck braces fall under which category? {
~Ancillary services #Ancillary services include lab tests, radiology, and pharmacy — not braces or orthotics.
=Durable Medical Equipment #Examples of DME include prosthetics such as artificial limbs and orthotics such as back and neck braces.
~Pharmaceutical supplies #Orthotics are classified as DME, not pharmaceutical supplies.
~Institutional provider services #Orthotics are equipment furnished by suppliers, not services from institutional providers.
}

::Q-PRV-043:: How much is the surety bond that a DMEPOS supplier must post per NPI to enroll in Medicare? {
~$10,000 #$10,000 is less than the required amount. The surety bond is $50,000 per NPI.
~$25,000 #$25,000 is less than the required amount. The surety bond is $50,000 per NPI.
=$50,000 #DMEPOS suppliers must post a $50,000 surety bond per NPI to enroll in Medicare.
~$100,000 #$100,000 is more than the required amount. The surety bond is $50,000 per NPI.
}

::Q-PRV-044:: Which enrollment form is used specifically by DMEPOS suppliers for Medicare? {
~CMS-855A #CMS-855A is the enrollment form for institutional providers such as hospitals.
~CMS-855I #CMS-855I is the enrollment form for individual physicians and non-physician practitioners.
=CMS-855S #DMEPOS suppliers enroll in Medicare using form CMS-855S, which is separate from the forms used by physicians or institutional providers.
~CMS-1450 #CMS-1450 is a billing claim form (also known as the UB-04), not an enrollment form.
}

::Q-PRV-045:: What condition must be met for Medicare to cover ambulance transportation? {
~The patient must be over age 65 #Age alone does not determine ambulance coverage; the medical necessity standard must be met.
~The patient must be traveling to an out-of-state hospital #Out-of-state travel is not the determining factor; medical necessity is.
=The patient's medical condition must make other transportation contraindicated #Medicare covers ambulance transportation only when the patient's medical condition makes any other means of transportation contraindicated.
~The patient must have a referral from a specialist #A specialist referral is not required; the determining factor is the patient's medical condition.
}

::Q-PRV-046:: When is Medicare air ambulance transport covered? {
~Whenever the patient requests it #Patient preference alone does not qualify for air ambulance coverage; medical necessity must be established.
~When the destination is more than 50 miles away #Distance alone is not the stated coverage criterion; the key factor is that ground ambulance cannot meet the need.
=When immediate transport is needed and ground ambulance cannot provide it #Emergency air ambulance transport is covered by Medicare when immediate transport is needed and ground ambulance cannot provide it.
~Only for patients enrolled in Medicare Advantage plans #Air ambulance coverage is not limited to Medicare Advantage; it applies to Original Medicare as well.
}

::Q-PRV-047:: Which of the following ambulance supplier types is covered under the Medicare ambulance fee schedule? {
~Only private ambulance companies #The fee schedule is not limited to private companies; it covers multiple supplier types.
~Only hospital-based ambulance services #Hospital-based services are included but are not the only type covered.
=Volunteer, municipal, private, independent, and hospital-based suppliers #The Medicare ambulance fee schedule applies to volunteer, municipal, private, and independent ambulance suppliers as well as institutional providers like hospitals.
~Only ambulance services operated by the federal government #The fee schedule applies broadly, not only to federal government-operated services.
}

::Q-PRV-048:: Which of the following is NOT classified as an ancillary service? {
~Laboratory tests #Laboratory tests are a standard ancillary service.
~Radiology services #Radiology is a standard ancillary service.
=Inpatient surgery #Ancillary services include laboratory tests, radiology, pharmacy services, and other diagnostic or therapeutic services that support primary care. Inpatient surgery is a hospital-based institutional service.
~Pharmacy services #Pharmacy services are a standard ancillary service.
}

::Q-PRV-049:: In which of the following settings can a clinical laboratory operate? {
~Only in hospitals #Hospitals are one of many settings; clinical labs also operate in physician offices, pharmacies, and other locations.
~Only in independent, stand-alone facilities #Independent labs are one of many settings, not the only option.
=In hospitals, physician offices, pharmacies, ambulatory surgery centers, and as independent labs #Clinical laboratories operate in many settings including hospitals, physician offices, pharmacies, ambulatory surgery centers, and as independent labs.
~Only in government-operated facilities #Clinical labs are not restricted to government facilities; they operate across both public and private settings.
}

::Q-PRV-050:: What is the electronic equivalent of the UB-04 (CMS-1450) institutional claim form? {
~837P #The 837P is the electronic equivalent of the CMS-1500, used by non-institutional providers.
=837I #Institutional providers use the CMS-1450 (UB-04) form or the 837I electronic transaction.
~835 #The 835 is an electronic remittance advice transaction, not a claim form.
~270/271 #The 270/271 transactions are used for eligibility inquiries and responses, not claims.
}

::Q-PRV-051:: Which law requires providers to submit Medicare claims electronically? {
~HIPAA Privacy Rule #The HIPAA Privacy Rule governs the protection of patient health information, not claims submission format.
~Affordable Care Act #The Affordable Care Act addressed insurance coverage expansion, not the mandate for electronic claims.
=Administrative Simplification Compliance Act (ASCA) #Providers are required to submit Medicare claims electronically under the Administrative Simplification Compliance Act (ASCA) unless they qualify for a waiver.
~Emergency Medical Treatment and Labor Act (EMTALA) #EMTALA requires hospitals to provide emergency care regardless of ability to pay, not electronic claims submission.
}

::Q-PRV-052:: What is PECOS in the context of Medicare enrollment? {
~A federal payment system for hospital claims #PECOS is an enrollment system, not a claims payment system.
=An online provider enrollment system #To enroll in Medicare, a provider completes an application through PECOS, the online enrollment system.
~A quality rating program for nursing homes #PECOS handles provider enrollment, not quality ratings.
~A prescription drug monitoring database #PECOS is for provider enrollment, not drug monitoring.
}

::Q-PRV-053:: What role does the Medicare Administrative Contractor (MAC) play in provider enrollment? {
~It issues the provider's medical license #Medical licenses are issued by state licensing boards, not MACs.
=It processes the provider's enrollment application after PECOS submission #The Medicare enrollment process involves obtaining an NPI, completing a PECOS application, and then working with the regional MAC, which processes the application.
~It assigns the provider's specialty designation #Specialty designations come from medical boards, not MACs.
~It conducts the provider's accreditation survey #Accreditation surveys are conducted by accrediting organizations, not MACs.
}

::Q-PRV-054:: How many digits are in a National Provider Identifier (NPI)? {
~6 #An NPI has 10 digits, not 6.
~8 #An NPI has 10 digits, not 8.
=10 #The NPI is a standard 10-digit number used to identify a provider across all health transactions.
~12 #An NPI has 10 digits, not 12.
}

::Q-PRV-055:: The NPI is used to identify a provider across which transactions? {
~Only Medicare billing transactions #The NPI is not limited to Medicare; it is used across all health transactions.
~Only Medicaid eligibility transactions #The NPI is not limited to Medicaid eligibility; it covers all health transactions.
=All health transactions #The NPI is a standard 10-digit number used to identify the provider across all health transactions.
~Only electronic pharmacy transactions #The NPI is not limited to pharmacy transactions; it is a universal identifier.
}

::Q-PRV-056:: Approximately how long does a paper Medicare enrollment application take to process? {
~14 days #14 days is significantly shorter than the actual processing time for paper applications.
~30 days #30 days is the approximate processing time for online PECOS applications, not paper submissions.
=65 days #Paper Medicare enrollment applications take approximately 65 days to process, compared to about 30 days for online PECOS applications.
~120 days #120 days is longer than the typical processing time for paper applications.
}

::Q-PRV-057:: Who administers the Medicaid provider enrollment process? {
~CMS directly, at the federal level #While CMS sets federal minimums, each state administers its own Medicaid enrollment process.
=Each state individually #Each state administers its own Medicaid provider enrollment process and may impose requirements beyond the federal minimums.
~The Joint Commission #The Joint Commission is a healthcare accreditation organization, not an enrollment administrator.
~Medicare Administrative Contractors #MACs process Medicare enrollment, not Medicaid enrollment.
}

::Q-PRV-058:: What must a state Medicaid agency confirm about a provider's license before enrollment? {
~That the license was issued within the last two years #There is no federal requirement about when the license was issued, only that it is unrestricted.
~That the license is from the same state as the Medicaid program #The requirement is that the license be unrestricted, not necessarily from the same state.
=That the license is unrestricted #State Medicaid agencies must verify that a provider holds an unrestricted license before approving enrollment.
~That the license includes a specialty certification #Specialty certification is not a federal Medicaid enrollment requirement; the key is an unrestricted license.
}

::Q-PRV-059:: Which of the following triggers a healthcare provider's status as a HIPAA-covered entity? {
~Having more than 50 employees #The number of employees does not determine covered-entity status; electronic transmission of health information does.
~Accepting patients with private insurance #Accepting private insurance alone does not trigger covered-entity status without electronic transmission of health information.
=Transmitting health information electronically in connection with certain transactions #Under HIPAA, a health care provider becomes a covered entity when it transmits health information electronically in connection with certain transactions such as claims billing.
~Operating in more than one state #Multi-state operations do not determine covered-entity status.
}

::Q-PRV-060:: Which HIPAA rule specifically requires safeguards to protect patient health information? {
~The Enforcement Rule #The Enforcement Rule addresses penalties for HIPAA violations, not the specific safeguard requirements.
~The Breach Notification Rule #The Breach Notification Rule addresses what to do when a breach occurs, not the primary safeguard requirements.
=The Privacy Rule and Security Rule #HIPAA-covered providers must comply with the Privacy Rule and Security Rule, which require safeguards to protect patient health information.
~The Transactions Rule #The Transactions Rule standardizes electronic transactions but is not the rule specifically requiring safeguards for patient information.
}

::Q-PRV-061:: HIPAA requires covered providers to train which group on protecting patient health information? {
~Only physicians #Training is required for all employees, not just physicians.
~Only IT staff #IT staff are included, but training is required for all employees.
=Employees #HIPAA-covered providers must comply with rules that require training for employees on protecting patient health information.
~Only billing department staff #Billing staff are included, but training is required for all employees.
}

::Q-PRV-062:: Which of the following healthcare entities is typically a HIPAA-covered entity? {
~A health food store #A health food store does not transmit health information electronically for covered transactions.
~A fitness center #A fitness center is not a healthcare provider that transmits health information electronically.
=A dentist's office #Most doctors, clinics, hospitals, psychologists, chiropractors, nursing homes, pharmacies, and dentists are HIPAA-covered entities because they transmit health information electronically.
~A medical textbook publisher #A medical textbook publisher does not transmit patient health information for covered transactions.
}

::Q-PRV-063:: Which of the following is a critical access hospital classified as under Medicare? {
~A supplier #Critical access hospitals are institutional providers, not suppliers.
~An ancillary service #A critical access hospital is a facility type, not an ancillary service.
=An institutional provider #Institutional providers include hospitals, critical access hospitals, skilled nursing facilities, home health agencies, and hospices.
~A non-institutional provider #Critical access hospitals are institutional providers, not non-institutional.
}

::Q-PRV-064:: Which of the following correctly matches the enrollment form to the provider type? {
~CMS-855A for physicians #Physicians use CMS-855I, not CMS-855A.
~CMS-855I for hospitals #Hospitals use CMS-855A, not CMS-855I.
=CMS-855S for DMEPOS suppliers #DMEPOS suppliers enroll using CMS-855S. Physicians use CMS-855I, and institutional providers like hospitals and hospices use CMS-855A.
~CMS-855S for hospices #Hospices are institutional providers and use CMS-855A, not CMS-855S.
}

::Q-PRV-065:: Which of the following is an example of a prosthetic device classified as DME? {
~A hearing aid battery #Hearing aid batteries are consumable accessories, not durable medical equipment.
=An artificial limb #Examples of DME include prosthetics such as artificial limbs, as well as orthotics, wheelchairs, hospital beds, and ventilators.
~A surgical scalpel #A surgical scalpel is a medical instrument used by clinicians, not patient DME.
~A disposable syringe #A disposable syringe is a single-use medical supply, not durable equipment.
}

::Q-PRV-066:: What type of organization must accredit a DMEPOS supplier before it can enroll in Medicare? {
~A state licensing board #State licensing boards issue licenses, but DMEPOS Medicare enrollment specifically requires CMS-approved accreditation.
=A CMS-approved accreditation organization #DMEPOS suppliers must obtain accreditation from a CMS-approved organization to enroll in Medicare.
~The Joint Commission exclusively #The Joint Commission is one potential accreditor, but the requirement is for any CMS-approved organization.
~The provider's regional MAC #The MAC processes enrollment applications but does not provide accreditation.
}

::Q-PRV-067:: DME must serve what kind of purpose to qualify? {
~A cosmetic purpose #Cosmetic purposes do not qualify equipment as DME.
~A recreational purpose #Recreational purposes do not qualify equipment as DME.
=A medical purpose #One of the defining criteria for DME is that it serves a medical purpose.
~An occupational purpose #While equipment may incidentally help with work, the qualifying criterion is a medical purpose.
}

::Q-PRV-068:: Which of the following is an example of oxygen equipment classified as DME? {
=An oxygen concentrator for home use #Examples of DME include oxygen equipment, which is prescribed for home use by patients with respiratory conditions.
~An oxygen tank used during surgery #Equipment used during surgery is part of the hospital's institutional services, not DME for home use.
~An air purifier for a waiting room #An air purifier is a consumer product, not medical DME.
~A nebulizer medication refill #A medication refill is a pharmaceutical product, not durable equipment.
}

::Q-PRV-069:: A skilled nursing facility is classified as which type of provider under Medicare? {
~A supplier #Skilled nursing facilities are institutional providers, not suppliers.
~A non-institutional provider #Skilled nursing facilities provide residential care and are classified as institutional, not non-institutional.
~An ancillary service provider #Ancillary services are diagnostic or therapeutic support services like labs and radiology, not residential facilities.
=An institutional provider #Institutional providers include hospitals, critical access hospitals, skilled nursing facilities, home health agencies, and hospices.
}

::Q-PRV-070:: Which claim form is used by institutional providers like hospitals to bill Medicare? {
~CMS-1500 #The CMS-1500 is used by non-institutional providers and suppliers, not hospitals.
=CMS-1450 (UB-04) #Institutional providers use the CMS-1450 form (UB-04) or the 837I electronic transaction to bill Medicare.
~CMS-855A #CMS-855A is a Medicare enrollment form, not a billing claim form.
~837P #The 837P is the electronic equivalent of the CMS-1500, used by non-institutional providers.
}

::Q-PRV-071:: Which of the following provider types bills using the 837P electronic transaction? {
~A hospital #Hospitals are institutional providers and use the 837I transaction.
~A skilled nursing facility #Skilled nursing facilities are institutional providers and use the 837I transaction.
=A physician office #Non-institutional providers and suppliers bill using the CMS-1500 or its electronic equivalent, the 837P transaction. Physician offices are non-institutional providers.
~A hospice #Hospices are institutional providers and use the 837I transaction.
}

::Q-PRV-072:: Under which circumstance might a provider be exempt from electronic Medicare claims submission? {
~If the provider is located in a rural area #Rural location alone does not exempt a provider from electronic submission requirements.
=If the provider qualifies for a waiver under ASCA #Providers are required to submit Medicare claims electronically under ASCA unless they qualify for a waiver.
~If the provider has fewer than 10 employees #The number of employees is not the determining factor; a waiver under ASCA is needed.
~If the provider only treats Medicare Advantage patients #Treating only Medicare Advantage patients does not create an exemption from electronic submission requirements.
}

::Q-PRV-073:: What is the correct order of steps in the Medicare provider enrollment process? {
~Apply through PECOS, obtain NPI, contact MAC #The NPI must be obtained before applying through PECOS, not after.
~Contact MAC, obtain NPI, apply through PECOS #Contacting the MAC is the final step, not the first.
=Obtain NPI, apply through PECOS, work with MAC #To enroll in Medicare, a provider must first obtain an NPI, then complete an application through PECOS, and finally work with their regional MAC.
~Obtain NPI, contact MAC, apply through PECOS #The PECOS application comes before working with the MAC, not after.
}

::Q-PRV-074:: Which type of provider furnishes sustained residential care under Medicare law? {
~A supplier #Suppliers furnish equipment, diagnostic, or therapeutic services — not sustained residential care.
=A provider (institutional) #Medicare law defines providers as institutional care facilities such as hospitals, hospices, and nursing homes that furnish sustained residential care.
~A clearinghouse #A clearinghouse processes electronic health transactions, not patient care.
~A business associate #A business associate handles health information on behalf of a covered entity but does not provide residential care.
}

::Q-PRV-075:: Which of the following services does a physician office NOT typically provide? {
~Outpatient diagnosis #Outpatient diagnosis is a core function of a physician office.
~Outpatient treatment #Outpatient treatment is a core function of a physician office.
=Inpatient overnight care #A physician office is a setting for outpatient evaluation, diagnosis, and treatment. Inpatient overnight care is provided by hospitals and similar institutional facilities.
~Patient evaluation #Patient evaluation is a core function of a physician office.
}

::Q-PRV-076:: Which of the following is a ventilator classified as? {
~An ancillary service #A ventilator is a piece of equipment, not a diagnostic or therapeutic service like lab tests or radiology.
~A pharmaceutical product #A ventilator is durable equipment, not a pharmaceutical product.
=Durable Medical Equipment #Examples of DME include ventilators, along with hospital beds, wheelchairs, oxygen equipment, prosthetics, and orthotics.
~An institutional service #While ventilators may be used in institutions, they are classified as DME when prescribed for patient use.
}

::Q-PRV-077:: Radiology services are classified under which category of healthcare services? {
~Institutional provider services #Radiology is a diagnostic service, not an institutional residential care service.
~Durable Medical Equipment #Radiology is a service, not a piece of durable equipment.
=Ancillary services #Ancillary services include laboratory tests, radiology, pharmacy services, and other diagnostic or therapeutic services that support primary care.
~Transportation services #Radiology is a diagnostic service, not a transportation service.
}

::Q-PRV-078:: Which of the following professionals is NOT specifically listed as a typical HIPAA-covered entity? {
~Chiropractor #Chiropractors are specifically listed as typical HIPAA-covered entities.
~Psychologist #Psychologists are specifically listed as typical HIPAA-covered entities.
=Personal fitness trainer #Typical HIPAA-covered entities include doctors, clinics, hospitals, psychologists, chiropractors, nursing homes, pharmacies, and dentists. A personal fitness trainer is not a healthcare provider.
~Dentist #Dentists are specifically listed as typical HIPAA-covered entities.
}

::Q-PRV-079:: What is the relationship between the CMS-1500 and the 837P? {
~The CMS-1500 replaced the 837P #The CMS-1500 did not replace the 837P. The 837P is the electronic version of the CMS-1500.
=The 837P is the electronic equivalent of the CMS-1500 #Non-institutional providers bill using the CMS-1500 claim form or its electronic equivalent, the 837P transaction.
~They are used by different provider types #Both are used by the same provider type (non-institutional); one is paper and the other is electronic.
~The CMS-1500 is used for institutional claims and the 837P for professional claims #The CMS-1500 is for professional (non-institutional) claims, not institutional claims. Institutional claims use the UB-04/837I.
}

::Q-PRV-080:: A business associate agreement is required under HIPAA between a covered provider and which party? {
~The patient #Patients are not business associates; providers give patients a Notice of Privacy Practices instead.
~The state licensing board #State licensing boards regulate licensure, not health information handling; they are not business associates.
=A business associate that handles health information on the provider's behalf #HIPAA-covered providers must have contracts with business associates — entities that handle protected health information on the provider's behalf.
~The provider's landlord #A landlord does not typically handle protected health information and would not be a business associate.
}

